<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Briefs Saudi Prince on Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat met Saudi Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz in Riyadh Tuesday to
brief him on the Palestinian-Israeli peace deal signed in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian diplomats told the Kuwait News Agency that Arafat
briefed Sultan, who is also second deputy prime minister and
defense and aviation minister, on the details of the nine-day
negotiations in Washington and the efforts made by U.S. President
Bill Clinton in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two leaders discussed the outcome of the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks and the Mideast peace process as a
whole, the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
Mediated by Clinton, Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu last Friday signed a land-for-peace deal to break the
19-month Mideast peace deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Israel will withdraw from another 13.1 percent
of the West Bank, in exchange for Palestinian revocation of the
call for Israel's destruction in its National Charter and
intensified crackdown on Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats said that during the talks, the Saudi prince
voiced his country's relief over the accord and hoped it will
enable the Palestinians to get their rights and establish their
state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived in Riyadh Monday, has already been to
Egypt, Algeria, Morocco and Tunisia to update their leaders on the
latest Palestinian-Israeli deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
