<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, October 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian security forces
announced Tuesday that they have arrested two Palestinians
suspected of killing a Jewish settler in the divided West Bank
town of Hebron Monday, local television reported.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the two had confessed to the murder and also
the killing of another Israeli man in a communal farm outside
Jerusalem about two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops enforced a curfew in the Israeli-controlled
part of Hebron Tuesday, barring about 30,000 Palestinians from
leaving their homes. Palestinians are even not allowed to go to
work or school.
</P>
<P>
The curfew, imposed Monday night after the slaying of Danny
Vargas, a 29-year-old security guard from the nearby Jewish
settlement of Kiryat Arba, was the third time since August that
the Palestinians in the Israeli-run sector of the city are not
allowed to go out. (Palestinians-Arrest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Gerhard Schroeder was sworn in as Germany's seventh
postwar chancellor on Tuesday after winning an election vote in
Germany's new parliament.
</P>
<P>
The new Bundestag, the lower house of parliament which was
formed on Monday, elected Schroeder by a vote of 351 to 287, with
27 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
He then received a letter of appointment from German President
Roman Herzog and took the oath of office in the Bundestag.
(Germany-New Chancellor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain said on Tuesday President Slobodan Milosevic
of Yugoslavia was making serious progress in the withdrawal of
troops from Kosovo's battlefronts but NATO should not drop its
guard.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to say there is some evidence that he (Milosevic)
is now making serious progress to deliver on his commitment and
our demand that he reduce his forces, both police and army, to the
levels before the conflict," British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
told BBC radio in an interview.
</P>
<P>
But Cook didn't say whether military action against Yugoslavia
would be necessary when the NATO deadline expires at 1900 GMT on
Tuesday. He said the alliance should keep up the
pressure. (Britain-NATO-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin arrived in the
Barvikha sanatorium from his Gorky-9 residence on Tuesday to
undergo "a course of rehabilitation treatment."
</P>
<P>
The duration of his stay in the sanatorium near Moscow will
depend on the treatment schedule, presidential spokesman Dmitry
Yakushkin said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, suffering irregular blood pressure and "serious
fatigue" in the wake of a bout of bronchitis, cancelled a planned
Tuesday trip to Austria, heeding doctors' advice that he take a
vacation.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov left for Vienna earlier on
Tuesday in place of Yeltsin for the summit between Russia and the
European Union. Austria currently holds the rotating EU
presidency. (Russia-Yeltsin-Health) 
</P>
</TEXT>
