<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for More Attention to African Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- China on Tuesday called
on the international community to give more attention to African
development as the world is moving towards globalization.
</P>
<P>
"We should not forget Africa," Shen Guofang, China's deputy
permanent representative to the United Nations, told a plenary
meeting of the 53rd General Assembly session, which on Tuesday
began to consider "the implementation of the United Nations New
Agenda for the Development of Africa in the 1990s."
</P>
<P>
"The economic situation in Africa has shown some improvements
over the past several years, thanks to the untiring efforts of
the vast number of African countries," he said, "But the overall
economic picture on the continent still looks grim."
</P>
<P>
The gap between the level of development in Africa and that of
the world is still widening, he said, adding that even if the
current growth rate is maintained, it will still take more than 10
years before Africa's per capita GDP can recover its 1980 level.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty is still ubiquitous" in Africa, he said, adding that
people living below poverty lines make up as much as more than
50 percent of the overall population in some African countries,
and indexes like the proportion of the population without access
to basic health and medical care, and the infant mortality rate,
are much higher in Africa than the world average.
</P>
<P>
"The debt burden remains heavy," he said. The overall volume
of external debt for African countries in 1996 amount to 320
billion U.S. dollars, equivalent to 70 percent of their GDP for
the same year, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Their precious resources have to be used for debt services
instead of being invested in national development," Shen said.
</P>
<P>
"There is still a severe shortage of development funds" in
Africa, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Official development assistance to Africa dropped from 14.2
billion U.S. dollars in 1992 to 12.8 billion U.S. dollars in 1996,
he said, adding that the already limited inflows of private
capital are also declining.
</P>
<P>
Primary commodity prices on international market continues to
fall, he said, adding that the prices for quite a number of
primary products dropped by over 10 percent in the past year,
bringing heavy losses to many African countries.
</P>
<P>
These "have shown that the major goals set in the New Agenda
are still far from being realized," Shen said, "The accelerated
economic globalization process has not brought a fair share of
benefits to African countries."
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, its negative impacts have proved costly to
them, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
