<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100 Million Africans to Face Mental Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 27 (Xinhua) -- An estimated 100 million people
in 46 African countries will suffer some mental illness mainly
because of poverty.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed at a meeting opened here Tuesday on the
strategy for mental health for African people.
</P>
<P>
Custodia Mandlhate, regional advisor of the World Health
Organization (WHO), said at the meeting the problems associated
with mental health were serious in Africa because they were not
given the priority they deserved by governments.
</P>
<P>
The two-day consultative meeting, attended by about 20
delegates from 12 African countries, seeks to contribute to the
change of the negative perceptions of mental disorders, combat
stigma and create appropriate services to resolve mental
problems.
</P>
<P>
A draft document on mental health and abuse of drugs will be
finalized at the meeting before it is delivered to the WHO
regional committee next year.
</P>
<P>
The document cites alcohol, tobacco and drug abuse as some of
the major problems being experienced in Africa because of
poverty, civil strife and displacement of families.
</P>
<P>
Mandlhate said the negative attitude of the media on issues
that dealt with mental health was another setback which left the
problems unaddressed, particularly among the poor.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting are health professionals from
Guinea Bissau, Benin, Mali, Togo, Botswana, Rwanda, Mauritius,
Nigeria, Sierra Leone, Tanzania, Uganda and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Concrete Steps to Aid African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The call came as Shen Guofang, China's deputy permanent
representative to the United Nations, was addressing a plenary
meeting of the 53rd General Assembly session, which on Tuesday
began to consider "the implementation of the United Nations New
Agenda for the Development of Africa in the 1990s."
</P>
<P>
"Economic globalization means that the interdependence between
the countries in the world has reached greater depths," he said,
"Sustained and healthy economic development in Africa is an
important condition for the continued stability and prosperity of
the world economy, and thus conforms to the long-term interests of
the international community as a whole."
</P>
<P>
The international community should dedicate itself to
establishing "a Partnership for Development for 21st Century" with
Africa, providing strong support to Africa and helping African
countries out of the vicious circle of economic under-development,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"African countries have emphasized on numerous occasions that
what Africa needs is neither preaching, nor new programs or plans
of action," he said, "What Africa needs is real action."
</P>
<P>
Concrete steps should be taken to help African countries
solve the key problems that are holding back their development
efforts, he said.
</P>
<P>
Shen put forward several proposals on international assistance
to African development:
</P>
<P>
-- To increase official development assistance to Africa and
loosens the conditions placed on such assistance, so that
African countries can use the resources more effectively in
accordance with the need and priorities of their own economic
and social development.
</P>
<P>
-- To step up implementation of measures like the "Heavily
Indebted Poor Countries" initiative, and relieve, in real terms,
the debt burden of African countries.
</P>
<P>
-- To remove trade barriers targeted at the developing
countries, to ensure greater market access for African products.
</P>
<P>
-- To encourage more productive investments and technology
transfers, with a view to helping African countries improve
their economic structures and enhance their competitiveness in
the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations should continue to play a pivotal role in
promoting development in Africa and in the effective
implementation of the New Agenda," Shen said.
</P>
<P>
Relevant institutions within the U.N. system should contribute
to the development of Africa by devoting sufficient resources,
and by formulating and implementing practical assistant programs
in the light of the specific characteristics of African
countries and their priorities for national economic
development, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
