<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Yugoslavia Complies With NATO Demands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Tuesday that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was in
"substantial compliance" with terms of the deal he accepted to end
the crisis over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"From watching the news reports, you can see there's been very
positive news there overnight and this morning," White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that thanks to NATO pressure and determination,
very substantial steps have been taken toward compliance," said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) had threatened
airstrikes unless Milosevic stops the fighting in Kosovo and pull
out all its forces out of the region. NATO sets the deadline at
19:00 GMT on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said that "Well over 90 percent of the security force
reinforcements" have been withdrawn, major road blocks have been
dismantled and heavy weapons have been returned to garrison.
</P>
<P>
"As we see this substantial compliance," Lockhart said, "we
also need to make sure that coming into compliance isn't the only
issue. We need to send the message that he needs to stay in
compliance."
</P>
<P>
He said that if the compliance is sustained, refugees will feel
secure to return home.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke also said
Tuesday that Yugoslavia is withdrawing substantial troops from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Serb security forces are pulling out. The international
verification regime is pouring in and the Serbs have suffered a
tremendous setback," he said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke and Milosevic reached a deal on October 13 in
Belgrade after marathon talks. Milosevic agreed to comply fully
with the U.N. demands, to move troops out of Kosovo and start
negotiations with the ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
