<HEADLINE> CBI Says Business Confidence in UK Plunging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) said Tuesday that business confidence in Britain is
plunging at its fastest rate for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
In its latest quarterly industrial trends survey, CBI painted a
gloomy picture of the state of the UK's manufacturing industry,
with business confidence falling to its lowest level since 1980.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that Britain's output is falling at its
fastest rate for seven years.
</P>
<P>
Adair Turner, Director-General of the CBI, said: "Combined with
the weaker growth now evident in other sectors of the economy,
this survey suggests a sharp downturn for the UK in the short
term, with an increased risk of outright recession."
</P>
<P>
So, Turner called on the Bank of England to cut interest rates
by 0.5 percent at its next meeting "to ensure the downturn is not
unnecessarily prolonger".
</P>
<P>
Neil Parker of the Royal Bank of Scotland said that the survey
was worse than the markets were expecting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
