<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Government Urged to Budget More for Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government came under
renewed pressure to aid the poor in its budget as the country's
most influential economic think-tank called on Tuesday for a boost
to welfare spending.
</P>
<P>
The Economic and Social Research Institute (ESRI) has joined
Ireland's largest union SIPTU and action group Combat Poverty in
calling for help for the country's poor.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent study of the United Nations, an estimated
one third of Irish people were living in relative poverty in 1995.
The ESRI said poverty would worsen if policies remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Whiel Ireland's economic boom has created busy industries in
the south, it has failed to bring significant wealth to the west.
</P>
<P>
"Recent budgets have favored high income earners... Social
welfare rates must rise in line with growth in other incomes if
the benefits of economic growth are to be spread more widely
across the community," ESRI said in its pre-budget submission.
</P>
<P>
Social welfare rates had risen by around 16 percent in the last
four years, lagging a 20 percent increase in average household
incomes as the Celtic Tiger's economy accelerated, Reuters quoted
ESRI as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ireland is the fastest growing economy in the European Union
but its wealth is spread unevenly and unemployment remaims high.
There is rising concern that large parts of the population are
failing to benefit, and are even suffering, from the boom.
</P>
<P>
The budget submission from ESRI adds to a growing consensus
among business, research and social groups in Ireland that the
country should tackle poverty and infrastrutual problems while its
finances are in an unusually buoyant state.
</P>
<P>
The government is forecasting a budget surplus of around 800
million punts (1.15 billion U.S. dollars) at the end of this year
but has warned against complacency in public spending, a point
echoed by ESRI which said the surplus should be maintained for
1999. The budget is expected to be announced on December 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
