<HEADLINE> Little Girl's Organs to Save Three Other Lives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Three Cypriot people are given
a new chance to live with the donation of organs after the tragic
death of a little girl, who was fatally injured in a riding
accident.
</P>
<P>
The three-year-old Vergina Nicolaides was critically injured on
Saturday when the pony she was riding on, during U.N. Open Day
celebrations at the U.N.-controlled Ledra Palace, bolted,
throwing her to the ground and trampled on her.
</P>
<P>
She was immediately taken to hospital in critical condition
and put on life support. But the girl was pronounced Monday night
brain-dead.
</P>
<P>
After her parents decided to donate their child's organs,
Vergina was taken to the Nicosia Paraskevaidion Transplant center
where her kidneys and liver were removed.
</P>
<P>
Doctor George Kyriakides, director of the center, said Tuesday
that the liver was already sent to London's Kings College
Hospital to be transplanted possibly to a Cypriot patient.
</P>
<P>
The kidneys are being transplanted to a seven-year-old boy,
Nicos Socratous and 49-year-old Christakis Efstathiou, both from
southern coastal town of Limassol.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Christos Stylianides on Tuesday praised
the child's parents for their courageous act to donate their
daughter's organs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
