<HEADLINE> Britain Warns Citizens against Travelling to Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Tuesday advised its
citizens not to travel to Chile unless absolutely necessary,
because anti-British feelings were running high after the arrest
of former Chilean President Augusto Pinochet in London.
</P>
<P>
Reuters quoted a Foreign Office spokesman as saying that
British citizens and commercial targets could become "targets for
mob violence", although no such attacks had taken place so far.
</P>
<P>
"We are advising against all non-essential travel to Chile
following the detention of General Pinochet. Feeling against
Britain and British nationals is running high in Chile," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is volatile and could change without warning
with British nationals and British commercial targets becoming
targets for mob violence," he said, adding Britons in Chile should
keep a low profile and avoid demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been isolated reports of abuse and physical
assault on people mistakenly identified as Britons, although no
British citizens or targets had been attacked.
</P>
<P>
Britain's High Court is due to decide on Wednesday whether a
Spanish request for Pinochet's extradition on murder and human
rights charges is lawful. The 82-year-old Pinochet has been under
guard in a London hospital since October 16.  
</P>
