<HEADLINE> World Spends $1.5 Billion Yearly on Polio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- A medical epidemiologist
from the World Health Organization (WHO) said here Tuesday if
polio were eradicated altogether from the world, an annual 1.5
billion U.S. Dollars would have gone into endeavors for social
development.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, O. Babaniyi, the
epidemiologist, made the remarks at a conference on polio
immunization campaign in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
He said although some countries in Latin America, North
America and Asia have succeeded in wiping out the disease, they
are forced to continue to spend large amount of money on the
production of polio vaccine because the ailment still surfaces
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The United States alone spends an annual 17 million Dollars on
the production of drugs and vaccination programs, said Babaniyi.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government has announced to eradicate polio by
2000. And the Ministry of Health plans to inoculate about 10
million children under five years of age in the last two months
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Some 7.3 million children received vaccinations in Ethiopia
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
