<HEADLINE> Demaci Says KLA to Show Restraint as Serb Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, Yugoslavia, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA) will show self-restraint as long as the Serb
side does not provoke the KLA, KLA's political representative Adem
Demaci said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At a regular press conference in Pristina, Demaci said Serb
troops did withdraw from Kosovo as demanded by the U.N.
resolution, but he was not sure whether the forces would return to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
When asked if the KLA will take over the villages and towns
after the Serb forces leave, Demaci said "the Albanian civilians
are KLA and the KLA are civilians."
</P>
<P>
"The KLA can't go to the sky. They are returning to their own
homes and houses as the Albanian civilians. This is not
take-over."
</P>
<P>
But he said the General Staff of the KLA has assured him "the
KLA will continue to show self-restraint as long as the Serb side
does not provoke the KLA and as long as it respects the agreements
between the KLA and the international verifiers on their positions
and emplacements."
</P>
<P>
The KLA, an outlaw military organization of the radical ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, declared a unilateral ceasefire on October
12, one day before an agreement was struck by Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke on Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Demaci stressed that no agreement on Kosovo would be accepted
by the KLA unless there was a clear provision in it, specifying
the date when the ethnic Albanians will exercise their right to
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian side demanded that Kosovo remain in the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia with higher autonomy for just three years
and a referendum be held on the future of the Serbian province.
Most of the ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of
Kosovo's 2 million population, want to have independence.
</P>
</TEXT>
