<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Calls for Calm After Killings in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu urged the Israelis Tuesday to keep "cool
heads", saying it is also a criminal act to murder people for
revenge, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were made one day after a Jewish settler and a
Palestinian man were killed in two murders in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The body of the 68-year-old Palestinian, Mohammed Zalmout, was
found outside a Jewish settlement near Nablus Monday afternoon,
several hours after Danny Vargas, a 29-year-old Jewish settler in
Hebron was shot dead.
</P>
<P>
An anonymous phone call to the Israeli army said the death of
Zalmout was a revenge killing.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian security forces announced Tuesday afternoon that
they have arrested two Palestinians suspected of killing Vargas. A
spokesman for the Palestinian General Intelligence Service in Gaza
said the two men were arrested in the morning in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the two had confessed to the murder and also
the killing of another Israeli man in a communal farm outside
Jerusalem two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces have described "very good" the
cooperation provided by Palestinian police since the shooting in
Hebron. They said they will also try to arrest an Israeli man
suspected of killing Zalmout as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Jewish settlers in the settlement where Zalmout's
body was found have given the Israeli army the name of the
suspected Israeli youth, who they said was not a resident in their
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Tibi, adviser to Palestinian National Authority Chairman
Yasser Arafat, told Israel Radio that the two Palestinians
arrested by police have denied connection to any organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army has expressed fear of a rapid escalation of
violence in the West Bank after the two killings. They said the
atmosphere in the areas was "extremely tense."
</P>
<P>
In the village where Zalmout had lived, Palestinian youth threw
stones at Israeli soldiers and the soldiers fired tear gas and
rubber bullets Tuesday. Several Palestinians were injured in the
clashes.
</P>
<P>
In Hebron, Israeli troops enforced a curfew in the
Israeli-controlled part of the town Tuesday, barring about 30,000
Palestinians from leaving their homes. Palestinians were even not
allowed to go to work or school.
</P>
<P>
The curfew, imposed Monday night after the slaying of Vargas,
was the third time since August that the Palestinians in the
Israeli-run sector are not allowed to go out.
</P>
<P>
The terror attacks have put the land-for-peace deal signed
by Netanyahu and Arafat at the White House last week to its
first test. They have also provoked concerns that extremist
actions might derail the peace process again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
