<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's New Government Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Germany's new government was sworn
in Tuesday evening after the German parliament formally elected
Gerhard Schroeder the country's seventh postwar chancellor.
</P>
<P>
The new government is a ruling coalition with Schroeder's
Social Democratic Party (SPD) sharing power with the much smaller
Greens party.
</P>
<P>
It is Germany's first center-left ruling coalition to include
the Greens, a party with roots in environmental and pacifist
movements in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Among the 15 ministerial posts in Schroeder's cabinet, 12 went
to the SPD, which replaced Kohl's Christian Democratic Union
(CDU)/Christian Social Union (CSU) conservative alliance as
Germany's strongest party after a victory in general elections on
September 27.
</P>
<P>
SPD Chairman Oskar Lafontaine will head an expanded finance
ministry with additional competence, such as Europe-related
economic policy, gained from the economics ministry
</P>
<P>
SPD parliamentary leader, Rudolf Scharping, will be defense
minister.
</P>
<P>
The Greens has won three ministerial posts with its leader
Joschka Fischer as foreign minister and vice-chancellor.
</P>
<P>
Werner Mueller, an independent and ex-manager of the VEBA
energy and telecom group, will head the economics ministry.
</P>
<P>
Five women have made their way into Schroeder's cabinet, but
only one eastern German, Christine Bergmann, has made it to be
family minister.
The full list of Schroeder's cabinet is as followings:

Federal Chancellor: Gerhard Schroeder (SPD)

Vice-Chancellor and Foreign Minister: Joschka Fischer (Greens)

Finance Minister: Oskar Lafontaine (SPD)

Defense Minister: Rudolf Scharping (SPD)

Economics Minister: Werner Mueller (independent)

Interior Minister: Otto Schily (SPD)

Justice Minister: Herta Daeubler-Gmelin (SPD)

Labour Minister: Walter Riester (SPD)

Transport and Construction minister: Franz Muentefering (SPD)

Environment Minister: Juergen Trittin (Greens)

Family, Seniors, Women and Youth Minister: Christine Bergmann (SPD)

Education and Research Minister: Edelgard Bulmahn (SPD)

Health Minister: Andrea Fischer (Greens)

Agriculture Minister: Karl-Heinz Funke (SPD)

Development Aid Minister: Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul (SPD)

Chancellory Minister: Bodo Hombach (SPD)
</P>
</TEXT>
