<HEADLINE> UK to Launch Bid to Promote 'Buy British' Message </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- British Government officials are
to meet retailers as part of an attempt to promote the sale of
home-grown food in British shops, according to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture, Food and Fisheries representatives
will discuss sourcing and pricing practices, with the aim to help
relieve the pressure on British farmers whose livelihood have been
hit by the "beef on the bone ban" and the downturn in global
economic markets.
</P>
<P>
Food Safety Minister Jeff Rooker said an announcement would be
made as quickly as possible on an aid package for farmers, according
to BBC.
</P>
<P>
Rooker said they were going through "an extremely difficult
period", with prospects not looking good for the immediate future.
The biggest market for British lambskins had been Russia, which had
now disappeared.
</P>
<P>
"However, we cannot order people to buy British," he said, in
response to calls for British food to be promoted.
</P>
<P>
The government have encouraged farmers to work together as
producers and not be isolated and picked off by those who control
the food markets.
</P>
<P>
But Conservative Agriculture Spokesman Tim Yeo said the
government was making matters worse for farmers, calling for the
lifting the ban on beef on the bone.
</P>
<P>
If the government did not lift it, there was a risk the European
Union would make it permanent, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
