<HEADLINE> Israeli Right Wings Urged to Halt Incitement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua)-- Senior Israeli politicians
urged the right wingers Tuesday to halt the wild incitement
campaign against Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman said it would be "very grave" if
there would be a repetition of the incitement waged against former
prime minister Yitzhak Rabin, who was assassinated by a right-wing
extremist in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Knesset (parliament) Speaker Dan Tichon opened the afternoon
plenum by a call for halting "all incitements."
</P>
<P>
Labor Party leader Ehud Barak, Meretz leader Yossi Sarid and
Yitzhak Levy, leader of the right-wing National Religious Party
which vehemently opposed the interim agreement, respectively
condemned the right-wing incitement campaign.
</P>
<P>
Jewish settlers and other right wingers have staged several
days of demonstrations in the West Bank and outside the prime
minister's residence in Jerusalem, protesting the
Israeli-Palestine agreement signed in Washington last Friday.
</P>
<P>
They accused Netanyahu of "betraying" his promises that he
would not give up any land to the Palestinians. Some called him "a
traitor," an accusation waged by right-wing extremists against
Rabin before he was murdered.
</P>
<P>
Security measures have been strengthened to protect Netanyahu,
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon and Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai since they returned from the U.S. talks Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the state attorney's office and police
met Tuesday to discuss the danger posed by political-motived
violence.
</P>
<P>
While continuing his effort to win approval for the agreement
by meeting with cabinet ministers, Netanyahu said Tuesday he
believes the opposition's move to hold early elections will not
succeed.
</P>
<P>
His remarks was boosted by a decision announced by six Arab
legislators of the opposition camp Tuesday afternoon that they
will not vote for the two bills calling for the dissolution of the
Knesset and holding early elections.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset Law Committee decided Monday to present the bills
to the plenum within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The bills passed in the preliminary reading in late July and
need to pass three more readings before becoming law. But their
chances for winning approval have become slimmer since the Arab
legislators announced their decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
