<HEADLINE> UK Says Lockerbie Bombers Must Be Jailed in Scotland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said Tuesday that Britain would insist that two suspects in
the Lockerbie bombing must serve their sentences in Scotland if
they were found guilty.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in British parliament Tuesday, Cook said: "We have
been able to respond positively to all the issues raised by the
Libyan legal team, with the exception of their demand that if
convicted the two accused should not serve their sentence in a
Scottish prison."
</P>
<P>
"If they are found guilty we see no reason why the two accused
should not serve sentence under the jurisdiction of Scotland,
where the mass murder took place," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook noted that Libya had not previously raised any concerns
about where the two men would serve their terms if found guilty
and "that concern only surfaced after we had met their demand for
a trial under Scottish law in a third country."
</P>
<P>
Britain and the United States announced in early August that
the trial of the two Libyan suspects could be held in the
Netherlands and the U.N. sanctions against Libya could be lifted
if Libya hands over the two suspects.
</P>
<P>
In December 1988, a Pan Am flight 103 blew up in mid-air over
the Scottish town of Lockerbie in December 1998, killing 270
people, most of them Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
