<HEADLINE> Volcano Erupts in War-Torn E. Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- A volcano near the strategic
town of Goma in eastern Congo (K) has gushed lava from its cone
and through a fissure in its side since October 17, causing great
concern for rebels.
</P>
<P>
A media report reaching here Tuesday said that lava flowing
from the Nyamuragira volcano is lighting up the night skies of
Goma, the eastern headquarters of rebels who launched a war
against President Laurent Kabila since early August.
</P>
<P>
"It is very active, but for the moment the lava flows are
diminishing," a senior official at the National Scientific
Research Center (CNRS) in Goma was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time lava has flowed from Nyamuragira since
December 1996, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Residents said light from the 3,056-meter high volcano had
reduced in recent days, but on Monday night a red glow was
visible north of the town.
</P>
<P>
The Nyamuragira is one of the two active volcanos in the
region. The other active volcano is Nyiragongo, which sits 3,470
meters high on the northern outskirts of Goma.
</P>
<P>
The chain of volcanic mountains which borders neighboring
Rwanda and Uganda also serves as a rear base of Rwandan Hutu
militiamen allegedly involved in the Rwandan genocide in 1994
when over 500,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
