Billy Rautenbach said his car plant would assemble 3,600 Volvo
S40 and V40 cars a year. The MCB entered into the pact with
Swedish Volvo Car Corporation in Gaborone.
</P>
<P>
No precise date was given for the start of assembly, but the
first Volvo car would roll off the line in early 1999, Rautenbach
said.
</P>
<P>
The deal is believed to be a significant boost for Botswana's
non-mineral export and diversification of the economy away from
its almost total reliance on diamonds, which is the backbone of
the country's current development policy.
</P>
<P>
For now, the MCB also assembles Hyundai cars of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Since the first exports of motor vehicles in 1993, the
Botswana car industry has grown to represent 60 percent of
Botwana's non-diamond export. In 1997, vehicles to the value of
1.058 billion Pula (about 263 million U.S. Dollars) were
exported.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of present vehicles exports are to South
Africa. 
