<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Postpones Cabinet Voting on Latest Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu decided Tuesday to postpone indefinitely a
cabinet voting on the latest deal he signed with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat last week, local television reported.
</P>
<P>
Aviv Bushinsky, spokesman for the prime minister, said that
the cabinet voting would not be held before the Palestinian
National Authority presents its plans to fight terrorism. The
voting was originally scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The latest land-for-peace deal inked in the White House should
be endorsed by the cabinet before going to the Knesset
(parliament) for approval. It also needs the blessing of the
Palestinian Council on the other hand.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the decision apparently in response to the
killing of a 29-year-old Jewish settler by Palestinian militants
Monday afternoon in the divided West Bank city of Hebron. The
settler was shot three times when driving home.
</P>
<P>
Several hours after the shooting, the body of a 68-year-old
Palestinian man was found outside a Jewish settlement near the
West Bank town of Nablus. An anonymous phone call called the death
of the Palestinian man a revenge killing.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu called on Israelis earlier Tuesday to keep "cool
heads," saying it was also a criminal act to murder people for
revenge.
</P>
<P>
The latest land-for-peace accord inked in the White House calls
on Israel to withdraw from 13 percent more of the West Bank in
exchange for specific Palestinian measures to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has said that only after the Palestinians fulfill
their security commitments would Israel carry out the phased
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces have described "very good" the
cooperation provided by Palestinian police since the shooting in
Hebron. Palestinian security forces announced Tuesday afternoon
that they have arrested two Palestinian suspects.
</P>
<P>
The terror attacks in the West Bank have put the new peace deal
to its first test and prompted concerns that extremist actions
might derail the peace process again. 
</P>
