<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Homicide Rate Down to Lowest Since 1969 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The homicide rate in Canada
declined 9 percent in 1997 to its lowest level point since 1969,
Statistics Canada said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The homicide rate has generally been decreasing since the
mid-1970s, following rapid growth during the late 1960s and early
1970s. There were 581 homicides in 1997, 54 fewer than in 1996,"
the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Canada's 1997 homicide rate of 1.92 per 100,000 population was
less than one-third that of the United States, but higher than
most European countries.
</P>
<P>
The statistics shows that the number of spousal homicides has
gradually declined from more than 100 each year in the early 1990s
to 75 last year.
</P>
<P>
And homicides continue to be committed primarily by someone
known to the victim. In 1997, only 13 percent of all victims were
killed by a stranger.
</P>
<P>
The surveys also show that the elderly have the highest levels
of fear of being a crime victim. However, in terms of homicides,
individuals aged 60 and older are actually at low risk.
</P>
<P>
In fact, people aged 18 to 29 had the highest homicide rate,
which was 3.39 for every 100,000 people. The lowest rate was for
children and young people aged 18 and under, the agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
