<HEADLINE> Air China, Northwest Airlines Begin Code-share Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 27 (Xinhua) -- China's flag carrier Air China
(CA) and U.S. Northwest Airlines (NW) began reciprocal code-share
service on Tuesday to increase efficiency.
</P>
<P>
CA will publish its code on NW's four-times-weekly flight New
York-Detroit-Beijing service, it was announced at a joint press
conference here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
CA will also code-share on U.S. domestic routes serving 17
cities according to agreement with Alaska Airlines, America West
and Continental Airlines.
</P>
<P>
NW will sell code-share service on CA's flights between Los
Angeles and both Shanghai and Beijing, and between San Francisco
and the same two Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
All of the above-mentioned flights operate four times weekly.
</P>
<P>
"This alliance offers NW the unique ability to offer convenient
flights via one-stop and two-stop itineraries between North
America and China," said Michael Levine, NW Executive Vice
President.
</P>
<P>
CA, China's largest airline, operates a fleet of 68 aircraft,
most of which are wide-body jets. It offers service on 42
international and regional routes to 39 cities in 28 countries in
addition to 61 domestic routes.
</P>
<P>
NW, the world's fourth largest airline and with its partner
carriers serve more than 400 destinations in 80 countries. It
operates a fleet of 417 aircraft including 35 Boeing 747 passenger
aircraft flying primarily in the Asia/Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The two carriers signed a code-share agreement on May 12, the
fist of kind between China and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
With the new partnership, CA, NW and its U.S. partners cover
close to 100 percent of all cities in the U.S., Canada, Mexico and
South America, and provide the greatest non-stop and one-stop
service between China and the U.S.. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
