<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Draft Cease-Fire Pact Reached on Congo (K) War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- African ministers Tuesday
adopted a draft cease-fire agreement here on the Congo (K) war
and a mechanism for implementing and monitoring the accord.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed in a press statement read at the closure of
the two-day closed-door meeting by Kaire Mbuende, Executive
Secretary of the Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Angola, Namibia, Zimbabwe and Uganda acknowledged their
military presence in the former Zaire, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe have sent thousands of their
troops to the largest central African country to assist Congolese
President Laurent Kabila in fighting against the rebels who now
hold large tracts of land in the east of the country.
</P>
<P>
While Uganda and Rwanda have been accused by Kinshasa of
invading to back the rebels to topple President Kabila, Rwanda
again denied direct involvement at the meeting, according to
informed sources.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was described as "very important" and
"successful" by Mbuende, also established a mechanism for the
involvement of the rebels in working out the modalities for the
implementation of the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time in the past months that the rebels have
been offered an opportunity to participate in the peace efforts
over the Congolese crisis.
</P>
<P>
Bizima Karaha, former foreign minister and now one of the
rebel leaders, told reporters outside the meeting venue Tuesday
afternoon that "the Congolese problem can only be resolved by the
Congolese people themselves."
</P>
<P>
He added that if the rebels were denied the opportunity of
getting involved in working out a mechanism to end the Congo (K)
crisis, all the efforts made in this field would be meaningless.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also resolved, through a mechanism involving
military experts to be established in the future, to address
those security concerns of Congo (K) and its neighbors, such as
Angola, Burundi, Rwanda and Uganda which explained in detail
their security concerns during consultations.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest gathering ever held to end the Congo (K)
war starting in early August. The meeting held in Zambian capital
Lusaka was chaired by Zambian Presidential Affairs Minister Eric
Silwamba and attended by defense and foreign ministers from 14
African countries including all the key players in the war such
as Zimbabwe, Namibia, Angola, Congo (K), Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also attracted Ibrahima Fall, U.N. Assistant
General for Political Affairs, Salim Ahmed Salim,
Secretary-General of the Organization of African Unity and the
senior officials from the SADC.
</P>
<P>
It focused on issues relating to the cessation of hostilities
in Congo (K), the establishment of a cease-fire and the
mechanisms for implementing it and the withdrawal of foreign
forces etc. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
