<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Govt Blamed for Detaining Suspects Too Long </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Minister of
Parliamentary Affairs Martin Aliker has said the government
accepts responsibility for detaining suspects for over 48 hours
without taking them to court.
</P>
<P>
He said this in response to a query by an MP as to why some of
his constituents were arrested and detained without appearing in
court, according to a Radio Uganda report Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The minister told Parliament Tuesday that this was an
oversight that will not be repeated.
</P>
<P>
When asked if detaining people in safe houses is provided for
in the Constitution, he explained that suspects are sometimes
kept in safe houses within police stations to protect them from
being molested by other prisoners.
</P>
<P>
According to Uganda's Constitution adopted in 1995, a suspect
must be led before judge within two days after his arrest. If no
official charges can be established against him, he should be
freed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
