<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Detainees on Rwandan Genocide on Hunger Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- As many as 25 detainees held
by the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) have
been on a hunger strike since Monday, the ICTR confirmed in a
statement reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR Registrar said he received a letter Tuesday signed by
25 hunger strikers out of the 32 detainees charging that the
Registrar denies their human rights in the assignment of defense
counsel to them.
</P>
<P>
All the strikers are on trial or awaiting trial for genocide
and other serious violations to international law committed in
Rwanda in 1994 when over 500,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus were
killed, said the statement from the ICTR headquarters in the
northern Tanzanian town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The first hunger striker, genocide convict Jean Paul Akayesu,
has not eaten since Thursday but his health was "quite
satisfactory," said tribunal spokesman Kingsley Moghalu.
</P>
<P>
Akayesu, sentenced last month to life imprisonment, is seeking
for a new defense counsel to lead his appeal. He was convicted of
genocide and anti-humanity crimes committed in the central
Rwandan commune of Taba, where around 2,000 ethnic Tutsis were
slaughtered in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Moghalu said the tribunal would not be brow-beaten by the
strike.
</P>
<P>
"We only hope that good sense will prevail. We will not be
intimidated," he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the tribunal has assigned 41 lawyers from all over
the world as defense counsel and co-counsel to the 32 detainees
in the Tribunal's custody in Arusha. Nearly all of these lawyers
have been chosen by the detainees themselves out of a list of
lawyers maintained by the Registry.
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal's projected expenditure for the payment of
defense lawyers in 1999 is over five million U.S. Dollars,
according to its statement.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal was established by the United Nations in November
1994 to bring to justice the main architects of the Rwandan
genocide. The only other convicted, Rwanda's former Prime
Minister Jean Kambanda, was also sentenced to life imprisonment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
