<HEADLINE> Mandela, Nujoma to Meet over Congo (K) Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 27 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela and his Namibian counterpart Sam Nujoma are due to
meet in Windhoek Wednesday, focusing on the crisis in Democratic
Congo (DRC), South African Press Association reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela was expected to appeal to Nujoma to rescind decisions
to deploy Namibian troops in the strife-torn Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
Unidentified South African officials were quoted as saying
that Mandela was not pleased with the recent decision by the
heads of state of Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe to take the war to
the areas controlled by Tutsi-led rebels in eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
They said Mandela wanted the Congo crisis to be resolved by
negotiations rather than force.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Nujoma, Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos and
Preside Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe announced in Harare that they
had decided to fight rebels in eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
Mandela reportedly was to meet the leader of the Congolese
rebel group, Ernest Wamba dia Wamba in Pretoria, capital of South
Africa, later this week.
</P>
<P>
According to Namibian officials, the Nujoma government was
also expected to discuss ways of strengthening trade and economic
ties with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, bordering with South Africa, has been dependent on
South Africa in terms of exports, earnings and imports.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Nujoma was also expected to raise the issue
of the South African-European Union Free Trade Area Agreement at
Wednesday's meeting. 
</P>
