<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: Saudi Crown Prince 7-Nation Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah
Ibn Abdul-Aziz returned home late Tuesday from a seven-nation tour
which is widely thought to be a diplomatic success, especially in
promoting bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, also Deputy Prime Minister and Commander of the Saudi
National Guard, began his seven-nation tour on September 13, with
Britain as his first leg, which was followed by France and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
After a two-week private vacation in Hawaii, the U.S.,
Abdullah flied on October 14 to China, the first stop of his
four-nation Asian tour which includes Japan, South Korea and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
During his 44-day visit, he discussed with leaders of these
states a broad range of bilateral, regional and international
issues.
</P>
<P>
While progress has reportedly been made in seeking common
grounds on policies toward those issues such as the deadlocked
Mideast peace process, the latest U.N.-Iraqi standoff, the
Afghan-Iranian crisis and terrorism, political observers here,
however, tend to credit the Saudi leader for his achievements in
developing bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah and French President Jacques Chirac have agreed to
strengthen their "strategic partnership," a proposal first
outlined in July 1996 when Chirac visited Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued at the end of his three-day visit,
both sides reaffirmed their countries' resolve to realize the
"partnership by boosting cooperation, especially in political,
economic and security fields."
</P>
<P>
They announced that a "detailed timetable" will be set for
talks on the strategic partnership.
</P>
<P>
As he was the highest-ranking Saudi official to visit China
since the two countries established diplomatic relations in 1990,
the week-long visit was attached special importance by both sides.
</P>
<P>
Both countries described the visit as "historic."
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum of understanding signed during the visit,
the two countries agreed to rapidly increase their trade and
economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, the Saudi Arabia promised to take in
more Chinese workers and technicians, especially in construction
industry and medical services.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, a major trade partner of Saudi Arabia in Asia,
Abdullah signed with Japanese Prime Minister Keizu Obuchi a
"landmark joint declaration to expand bilateral relations in the
21st century."
</P>
<P>
The two leaders underscored during their talks the healthy
bilateral ties and expressed desire to boost them by promoting
political dialogue and establishing extensive economic links.
</P>
<P>
In his last leg in Pakistan, Abdullah and Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif agreed to give new impetus to bilateral relations by
enhancing cooperation in various fields, including trade,
investment and joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
In addition to achievements in boosting bilateral ties, broad
consensus was also reached on regional and international matters
of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also reach consensus with the leaders of the host
countries that the Iraqi government should resume cooperation
with the U.N. weapons inspectors and fully comply with the
Security Council resolutions related to its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The leaders, at the same time, expressed sympathy with the Iraqi
people suffering from the U.N. economic sanctions imposed after
its invasion.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, together with the leaders of the host states,
denounced all kinds of terrorism and stressed that the issue be
tackled under leadership of the U.N..
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also reportedly gained support from some his Asian
hosts on efforts to limit and finally remove weapons of mass
destruction in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
While immediate effect is hard to predict, foreign diplomats
here believe that the visit by Abdullah, both Gulf and Arab
heavyweight, is in general very positive to security and
stability in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
