<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Expected to Strengthen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan Shilling changed
little against the U.S. Dollar Tuesday but expected to strengthen
slightly on inflows from the tea and coffee sectors, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) posted the Shilling at a mean
commercial rate of 59.7889, unchanged from Monday.
</P>
<P>
But traders expected that Dollars will flow into the foreign
exchange market from the tea and coffee export auctions Mondays
and Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
Signs of the Shilling strength also came from the central
bank, which said it was buying Dollar notes at 57.96 Shillings
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank posted the Pound at a mean commercial rate of
99.6898 compared to 100.5458 on Monday. CBK said it was buying
pound notes at 96.63 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, a senior dealer said that there is still limited
activity in the market.
</P>
<P>
"We have not drastically moved from the position on Monday.
Sentiment is still for a stronger shilling," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Commercial dealers said margins had declined to between five
and 10 cents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
