<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Postpones Cabinet Voting on Latest Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu decided Tuesday to postpone indefinitely a
cabinet voting on the latest deal he signed with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat last week, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu reportedly decided that the vote would not be held
until the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) submits to the
United States its plans to fight terrorism. The vote had been
originally scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The latest land-for-peace deal inked in the White House should
be endorsed by the cabinet before going to the Knesset
(parliament) for approval. It also needs the blessing of the
Palestinian Council on the other hand.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that according to the understanding reached
between Israel and the Palestinians, the PNA should present a
concrete plan for fighting terrorism to Washington within a week
after the signing of the accord.
</P>
<P>
The deal was signed last Friday at the White House. It calls on
Israel to hand over a further 13 percent of the West Bank in
exchange for intensified and specific Palestinian measures to
fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday Netanyahu also met with members of his "inner
cabinet" - Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai and Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky
- to discuss a statement made by senior Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat on the Palestinian National Charter, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and his ministers expressed concern over Erekat's
statement that the Palestinian National Council (PNC) would not
revise the charter calling for the destruction of Israel, it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest land-for-peace deal, the PNC would
convene to revoke the anti-Israel provisions in the charter. But
the radio did not say when Erekat made the statement or what he
exactly said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's decision also came a day after a Jewish settler
was killed by suspected Palestinian militants Monday afternoon in
the divided West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian man was murdered several hours later outside a
Jewish settlement near Nablus in what was called a "revenge
killing."
</P>
<P>
The terror attacks have put the new peace deal to its first
test and prompted concerns that extremist actions might derail the
peace process again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
