<HEADLINE> S. African Ruling Party Angry Over Truth Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 27 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) is angry over the final report of
the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC), which is set to
implicate it in human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
The ANC accused the commission of criminalizing the liberation
movement in the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever the efforts to besmirch our struggle by denouncing
it as gross violation of human rights, the ANC, Umkhonto we Sizwe
(military wing of the ANC meaning Spear of the Nation) and the
millions of people who were part of this struggle will always be
proud of what they did to ensure that, in the process of the
destruction of a vile system, they do not themselves resort to
vile methods of struggle on the basis that the means justified
the end."
</P>
<P>
The ANC said the TRC findings against it were "capricious and
arbitrary" and contrary to fundamental principles of
international law.
</P>
<P>
The ANC was responding to a section 30 notice outlining the
commission's anticipated findings that the ANC was morally and
politically responsible for gross human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
The 3,000-page report will be handed over to South African
President Nelson Mandela in Pretoria Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The TRC sent about 200 notices to various parties and
individuals, informing them that they were likely to be
implicated to their detriment, and asking for responses.
</P>
<P>
Former President F. W. de Klerk has asked the high court in
Cape Town for an interdict to withhold sections of the report,
which would implicate him in illegal actions by the apartheid
government.
The case has been set down Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
