<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Not to Bomb Yugoslavia But to Maintain Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NATO decided on October 13 to issue activation orders for a
limited air strike and a phased air campaign against Yugoslavia in
order to back up diplomatic efforts to achieve peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Western military alliance extended on October 16 the
ultimatum by 10 more days until this Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that the activation orders had kept Belgrade under
pressure and it was the pressure and NATO's threat to use force
that had changed the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We have been able to reduce the level of violence
significantly and to achieve a cease-fire which has held, despite
some sporadic incidents," said Solana.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief described the improvement in the security
situation in Kosovo as having allowed an immediate improvement in
the humanitarian situation.
</P>
<P>
NATO's aerial surveillance and the Kosovo diplomatic observer
mission verified the withdrawal by the Belgrade side.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that NATO's next focus would be on ensuring the
effectiveness of the verification process.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
announced that the verification mission would last for a year in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The North Atlantic Council will keep the situation in Kosovo
under constant review. If we see evidence of substantial
non-compliance in the future with UNSCR 1199 then we will be ready
to use force," Solana said.
</P>
<P>
"We know that (Yugoslav) President (Slobodan) Milosevic only
moves when he is presented with the credible threat of force," he
said.
</P>
<P>
NATO forces are instructed to maintain at appropriate readiness
levels for the operations under both activation orders.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that the council requested the NATO military
authorities to remain prepared to carry out the air operations
should they become necessary.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief also urged Kosovar ethnic Albanians to equally
comply with the UNSCRs and cooperate with the international
community.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Kosovo crisis was far from over and a lot of
work remained to be done.
</P>
<P>
"It is high time that the Serbs and the Kosovar Albanians
understand that the international community will not tolerate a
continuation of the status quo," Solana said.
</P>
<P>
"There has been too much human suffering," he added.
</P>
<P>
NATO observers believed that the last-ditch mission by two NATO
senior officers to Belgrade Saturday and Sunday contributed to the
de-activation and an open-ended extension of the strike orders.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook described Monday the
agreement reached between NATO Military Committee Chairman Klaus
Naumann and Supreme Allied Commander Europe Wesley Clark and
Belgrade as a significant advance, though no detail of their
mission was disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
