<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader Addresses Elderly Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Vice-President Hu Jintao, on
the Double Ninth Festival, a traditional Chinese holiday for
showing respect to the elderly, used a China Central Television
address today to praise the elderly and mark the 1999
International Year of Older Persons.
</P>
<P>
China has 120 million people above the age of 60, and that
number is expected to reach 130 million by the year 2000, and to
be around 400 million by the middle of the next century.
</P>
<P>
Family structure and social changes resulting from the growing
number of elderly are having a great impact on the economy and
social development. All of society needs to be more aware of the
problem and to concentrate on ways to deal with it, said Hu, who
is also a member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau
of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
China's elderly have made a great contribution to the country's
development, Hu said, and they deserve the respect of all of
society and society should take care of its senior citizens, and
see that they get a fair share of the fruits of the reforms and
opening up.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese, united around the CPC Central Committee with Jiang
Zemin at the core, are pushing the great cause of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics forward, holding high the
great banner of Deng Xiaoping Theory, Hu said, and he hopes that
the elderly will be able to contribute even more to the
drive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
