<HEADLINE> Quebec Premier Expected to Call Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard
is expected to call a general election in Canada's French-speaking
province of Quebec later this month.
</P>
<P>
Bouchard is set to meet his cabinet Wednesday and have it adopt
a decree that is required to dissolve Quebec's National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday afternoon, he is expected to complete the process
of calling the vote, which will be held on November 30.
</P>
<P>
Bouchard said his career was on the line as he prepared to call
the election, which would determine the futures of Quebec and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
"I know very well, it is certain, that my career is at stake,
my political career. It's obvious. This is a moment of truth for
me," he was quoted as saying by the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The 59-year-old Bouchard, who has been leader of Parti
Quebecois (PQ) and premier of the province since early 1995, said
that if re-elected, he would work towards holding another
referendum on Quebec's secession from Canada.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming campaign would be "nasty" and "no-holds-barred",
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The two major parties, the independence-oriented PQ and the
pro-Canadian Liberal Party, are neck and neck in popular support.
</P>
<P>
The latest opinion poll released Tuesday showed that 45 percent
of Quebec respondents plan to vote for the Liberals, and 44
percent for the PQ.
</P>
<P>
Liberal leader Jean Charest also said there were high stakes on
his side. "I'm heading into the biggest political fight of my
life.
</P>
<P>
"The battle will be close, the campaign will be tough, and I
expect it to be very intense," said 40-year-old Charest, who
entered Quebec provincial politics early this year when there was
a call for him to fill the Liberal leadership void.
</P>
<P>
Support for the Liberals surged to 52 percent in April after
Charest's move, but has dwindled steadily over the summer, which
was worrying for people who once viewed Charest as a savior of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the campaign, which is expected to focus on
the referendum, economy and health-care, will be closely followed
by people of not only Quebec but the rest of Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
