<HEADLINE> Village Autonomy Vs. Party And Government Control (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Many lawmakers said they were delighted to see that the recent
draft mentioned the sensitive and delicate relations between the
Chinese Communist Party village branches and autonomous villagers'
committees.
</P>
<P>
It says that Party branches are to play a leading role in rural
work in accordance with the CPC Constitution and regulations, but
they must strictly abide by the country's Constitution and
national laws to protect the democratic rights of villagers and
self-government.
</P>
<P>
Some legislators said that this relationship needs to be
clarified and that a phrase like "related regulations" that the
draft uses is too ambiguous, because all Party committees may
produce "related regulations".
</P>
<P>
Sui Yongju questioned the "leadership role" of the Party
branches in the rural work and asked whether it meant that Party
branches lead villagers committees, and if so, then it should be
clearly stated, and if not, then removed.
</P>
<P>
The amendment to the 10-year-old Organic Law has been published
to guage public opinion.
</P>
<P>
A revision is expected to change election and impeachment
procedures of village heads, daily operation rules of villagers
committees, and expand the rights of villagers.  
</P>
