<HEADLINE> Revised Draft Of Chinese Highway Law Proves Controversial (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A revised draft of the Highway
Law submitted to the 5th meeting of the Standing Committee of the
Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) caused quite an argument
today.
</P>
<P>
The draft says that highway maintenance and other levies can be
replaced by revenues from gasoline sales and an automobile sales
tax to help stop illicit fees.
</P>
<P>
But, members of the NPC Standing Committee said that this would
affect the local government finances even if a crackdown on
illicit fees is necessary.
</P>
<P>
They said that it could also put an unreasonable burden on
enterprises and farmers and result in gasoline smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Ruan Chongwu said that the purpose of the new measure is to
change local fees into central financial revenues and that central
government departments could allocate revenues. But this in fact
strengthens the power of central departments, he said, and local
governments would have to lobby the capital to get financial aid
and that this is not helpful to building an honest and clean
government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
