<HEADLINE> Solana: Political Settlement of Kosovo Crisis Still Far Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, October 28 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana said Wednesday that there is still a long way to go before
a political settlement of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on a Spanish radio, Solana said that NATO must seek a
political settlement of the Kosovo conflict in a most urgent way,
after giving up immediate air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Reaching an agreement on the "establishment of a self-rule
government in the Kosovo region" should be the goal of the
political settlement sought by NATO, he said.
</P>
<P>
What NATO has done so far was only to end the most violent part
of the conflict in the province, but the final goal is to
implement all relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
NATO announced Tuesday there would be no immediate air strikes
against Yugoslavia after confirming that the number of Yugoslav
security forces in Kosovo had returned to the pre-conflict level,
a key demand of NATO for abandoning military strikes.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past 24 hours, over 4,000 members of the (Serb)
special police have been withdrawn from Kosovo. Police and
military units based in Kosovo are moving back to their barracks
with their heavy weapons," Solana said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But Solana also threatened Tuesday that NATO might consider the
military option again if Belgrade failed to fully comply with
international demands for an end to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 international monitors will enter Kosovo soon with
Serbian approval to verify demilitarization, help refugees
resettle safely and foster a climate for talks on self-government
for Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
