<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Launches Six-month Campaign Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has launched a six-month
campaign against the Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS)
in compliance with the United Nations 1998 World AIDS Campaign.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing in Nigerian capital Abuja, Alhaji Tukur
Mani, Permanent Secretary of the Ministry of Health, said Tuesday
his ministry would adopt an Expanded National Response Strategy
to combat the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
"This new initiative is informed by the realization that
HIV/AIDS problem goes beyond what the Ministry of Health can
handle alone," he was quoted by Wednesday's The Punch newspaper
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new strategy will involve six ministries, namely,
ministries for health, information and culture, education,
federal capital territory, women affairs and youth and sports.
</P>
<P>
The health official noted that the Health Ministry had
budgeted 30 million Naira (about 330,000 U.S. Dollars) for the
publicity of the campaign while the Petroleum Trust Fund had made
a provision of 800 million Naira (about 8.9 million Dollars) for
HIV/AIDS control in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that in 1998 more than 360,000 new HIV infections
would be recorded among Nigerians and an average of 1,000
Nigerians are infected daily.
</P>
<P>
So far, Mani said, three million Nigerians or 4.5 percent of
its sexually-active population had already contacted the disease
by the end of 1997 with 530,000 killed by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
AIDS control drugs are available at the local market, he said,
adding that the drugs cost AIDS victims between 30,000 Naira and
50,000 Naira (about 450 Dollars) which is far beyond the reach of
majority of those infected with HIV/AIDS in Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highway Law Controversial (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition, Ruan said, many highways are built by local
revenues or even by private enterprises and overseas investors
and if the central government collects gasoline taxes, the local
government, private enterprises, and overseas investors will have a
problem getting their fair share back.
</P>
<P>
The new measure was drawn up by the ministries of
communications and finance after studying the practice on Hainan
Island, which has replaced tolls with taxes.
</P>
<P>
Li Yining, a professor at Beijing University, says that a
change would certainly put a burden on farmers and
enterprises. Most agricultural machinery used by farmers, for
example, can not use the highways, so it is unreasonable to tax it
for highway maintenance, he said, and factories that need gasoline
but don't use highways will face the same problem.
</P>
<P>
Gu Jinchi, said that China's oil is priced higher than that on
the international market, and the new measure may lead to gasoline
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Ruan Chongwu also said that the local government is now
involved in a fight against gasoline smuggling because it affects
their economy and if revenues from gasoline go to the central
revenues, local governments will have no enthusiasm for continuing
the fight against gasoline smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The revised draft of the Highway Law will be submitted to the
5th meeting of the Ninth NPC Standing Committee, so that it is
expected to go into effect on January 1, 1999. 
</P>
