<HEADLINE> NBA Talks May Draw Crowd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The NBA players union is
gearing up for another show of solidarity Wednesday during a
collective bargaining session with the league.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 of the union's 411 members attended a general
meeting last week in Las Vegas. Union executive director Billy
Hunter expects 200-300 players to attend Wednesday's session,
which will be held following the league's board of governors
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Those players who failed to appear in Las Vegas feel they
missed out on a great moment, when all the players came
together," Hunter said. " As a result, they're all flying in. The
numbers could easily exceed what we had in Las Vegas."
</P>
<P>
Hunter said Michael Jordan, David Robinson and Karl Malone
again would be at the meeting as well as Grant Hill and Tim
Duncan, who were no-shows in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
"The intent is to meet with the owners," Hunter said. "In Las
Vegas the players were of the mind if they were present they
could bring some impetus and demonstrated that we're together,
we're unified and we're not going to accept a bad deal. If they
have to hear that from 200-some ballplayers to get the message,
that's what we intend to bring."
</P>
<P>
The players voted unanimously last week never to accept the
hard salary cap owners proposed and said they would be willing to
sit out the season.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner David Stern has canceled the first two weeks of
the season, 99 games, and could cancel more Wednesday or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We need a session to let them know where we are and to let
them know what we have done," union vice president Dikembe
Mutombo said. 
</P>
