<HEADLINE> EU Takes Measures to Curb "Mad Cow Disease" in Portugal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
announced Wednesday a series of urgent measures to address the
risk of "mad cow disease" for humans and animals both inside and
outside Portugal.
</P>
<P>
The measures include an action program to enforce all European
Union (EU) and Portuguese national measures against the disease, in
particular the removal of specified risk material, as well as a
total ban on the feeding of meat and bone meal.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, a ban on exports of meat and
meat products which expires in nine months will be proposed. So
will be another ban on exports of live animals which will be
reviewed within 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The Commission, the EU's executive body, said it will provide
financial support for measures taken by Portugal in fighting
Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE), known as "mad cow disease."
</P>
<P>
So far this year, a total of 67 cases of BSE have been notified
in Portugal, including two cases in animals born after the
implementation of the ban on the feeding of mammalian derived
proteins to ruminants.
</P>
<P>
Insufficient implementation of the measures to control BSE risk
factors, together the increased cases of mad cow disease since
June, raised serious concerns regarding to the development of the
disease, the Commission said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
