<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIVB to Use New Scoring System from 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The world volleyball's governing
body FIVB approved unanimously on Wednesday a proposal to use a
new scoring system from January 1999 in all FIVB competitions.
</P>
<P>
The main change will be that teams score points at each rally
in the style of current tie-breaks, not only when a team has
served, the FIVB said.
</P>
<P>
Matches will be played in the best of five sets format with 25
points for the first four sets and 15 points for the fifth set,
each of them with a minimum lead of two points.
</P>
<P>
The new system will be used in the men's World League, the
women's Grand Prix, the junior and youth world championships and
the World Cup as well as in the continental championships in 1999.
</P>
<P>
National federations are free to introduce it in 1999, but it
will become compulsory at all levels from January 2000, including
the Sydney Olympic Games, the FIVB said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
