<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Merapi Volcano's Hot Cloud May Come up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The activities of Indonesia's
Mount Merapi at the Central Java have been given "Alert Merapi"
status, meaning that alertness upon the threats of hot cloud and
volcanic mudflow should be maintained.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Center for Research and Development of Vulcanology
Technology in Yogyakarta Mas Atje Purbawinata said on Wednesday
that the spurt of hot cloud and the flow of lava from the top of
Mount Merapi may happen at any time.
</P>
<P>
In October 1998, this most active volcano mountain in Indonesia
has spurted hot cloud for a number of times, directed at the Kali
Lamat river's upstream with a maximum distance of 1.2 kilometers,
Mas Atje was quoted by Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Visual monitoring shows that the solfatara (sulphur) smoke
coming out of Mount Merapi has a white thin to thick hue, low
pressure and a maximum height of 50 meters from the top of the
mountain.
</P>
<P>
The drop of red-hot lava has continued with a maximum flow of
0.9 kilometer.
</P>
<P>
The seismic activities of Mount Merapi this week have been
dominated by surface earthquakes, namely multi-phase earthquakes
indicating the vibrations of the growth of lava dome and the drop
of red-hot lava, Mas Atje added.
</P>
<P>
The 2,968-meter high Mount Merapi last erupted on July 11,
spilling out hot fumes and ashes.
</P>
<P>
Three major eruptions have been recorded in the past, the most
of which occurred in 1930 when 1,300 people were killed. The other
two eruptions were in 1994 and 1977, when a total of 88 people
died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
