<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO-Led Air Surveillance to Start Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- NATO is expected to give the
go-ahead to the air surveillance in Kosovo as soon as the end of
this week, a NATO official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that
NATO's decision-making body, the North Atlantic Council, would
meet on Friday to approve the air-borne surveillance mission.
</P>
<P>
"The air surveillance is expected to be approved as rapidly as
possible, but sufficient measures have to be in place to protect
the NATO surveillance planes that are unarmed," said the official.
</P>
<P>
NATO on Tuesday suspended its air strike operation against
Yugoslavia after the country met the troop withdrawal deadline by
pulling out another 4,000 soldiers and policemen from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said that the allies would
rely on air and ground verification of the compliance with United
Nations Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
NATO decision makers will also discuss and decide on the
deployment of extraction forces in a nearby location as the backup
for the 2,000-member verification mission to be led by the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
The same official said that the agreement reached between
Belgrade and OSCE put the responsibility for ensuring the safety
of the verification monitors on the shoulders of Yugoslav
authorities.
</P>
<P>
But OSCE Chairman Bronislaw Geremek reportedly said on
Wednesday that the task of guarding the safety of monitors also
lies in the hands of NATO.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Council is scheduled to discuss the
deployment of extraction forces on Friday and the mission of the
NATO-led forces.
</P>
<P>
The official declined to comment on the size and location of
the extraction force. Some press reports suggested that the force
would be deployed in Macedonia, next to the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The official, however, admitted that there was a direct link
between the deployment of extraction forces and the deployment of
the unarmed monitors in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He quoted a United Nations Security Council resolution as
saying that the OSCE and NATO could take appropriate action to
ensure the safety of the monitors.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE announced on Sunday that the verification mission
would last for a year.
</P>
<P>
The NATO official urged ethnic Albanians in Kosovo to make the
most of the ceasefire to further the political process, but he did
not think that the November 4 deadline for starting the political
process would be met. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
