<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Humanitarian Disaster Averted, Says USAID Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, Yugoslavia, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The humanitarian
disaster that has loomed for months in Yugoslav province of Kosovo
has been averted, a United States Agency for International
Development (USAID) official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Based on my revisit to Malishevo, Dragobila, and the Pagarusha
area (in Kosovo), plus conversations with NGOs (non-governmental
organizations), international organizations, and our own disaster
assistance relief team, I believe we can say that the humanitarian
disaster we all feared has been averted," Hugh Parmer, assistant
administrator for USAID, said.
</P>
<P>
He said he saw a constant stream of people returning to their
villages in the area surrounding Pagarusha on Tuesday, and hoped
that the current level of security on the ground would be
maintained so that more displaced persons could return home.
</P>
<P>
However, Parmer said this was no time to declare a humanitarian
victory. The coming weeks and months would still be difficult for
the displaced people, he stressed, but "if efforts are maintained
and access provided, there will be no disaster."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR) said more than 200,000 people in Kosovo were displaced due
to the seven-month conflict and feared that thousands of people
living in the open would possibly die of cold as winter approached.
</P>
<P>
Parmer said the resolve of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) to keep pressure on Yugoslav leaders had
helped improve the situation of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
NATO on Tuesday extended its deadline of military threat on
Yugoslavia, which expired Tuesday afternoon, indefinitely after
international observers confirmed that most Serb forces had pulled
out of Kosovo on Monday or returned to their barracks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
