<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo to Remain in Serbia, Says Kosovo Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, Yugoslavia, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Kosovo province is
part of Serbia and any kind of secession is unacceptable, Kosovo's
top official Zoran Andelkovic said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking exclusively to Xinhua in his office in Pristina,
President Andelkovic of the Temporary Executive Council of Kosovo,
said the Serbian government was "ready to grant highest autonomy"
to Kosovo on the principle that all nationalities were equal
without discrimination.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Kosovo's status could be equal to that of Serbia and
Montenegro, as demanded by ethnic Albanians, Andelkovic said
firmly that the secession of Kosovo from Serbia was the "de facto
splitting of the state of Yugoslavia," which was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, ethnic Albanian leaders proposed to solve the Kosovo
crisis within Yugoslavia, but not within Serbia, a demand for the
province to be given equal status to Serbia and Montenegro, the
two republics that make up the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
However, Andelkovic said he was confident the Serbs and
Albanians in Kosovo could still live together peacefully after
resolving the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"They have lived here for centuries and have never had problems
before," the de facto provincial governor said, "If the Albanians
here proclaim they can't live with Serbs and want to create their
own state, then thousands of states can be created in the world."
</P>
<P>
Andelkovic said huge efforts had been made to diminish the
plight of refugees with the establishment of 16 humanitarian
centers with 92 aid distribution centers to provide relief.
</P>
<P>
"I am ready to find any refugees living in the open or
temporary shelter, talk to them and settle them in houses wherever
they wish to settle. We don't have problems with these
civilians. We only have problems with terrorists," he said,
referring to ethnic Albanian separatists.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees said
more than 250,000 people have fled their homes to escape the
conflict in the past seven months and a humanitarian catastrophe
was looming as winter approached.
</P>
<P>
But the top official in Kosovo designated by the Serbian
government said Western countries were only interested in
humanitarian issues as an excuse to interfere into Yugoslavia's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly 700,000 Serbs were expelled from their own territories
in Krajina in the former Yugoslav Republic of Croatia in 1995 and
they never have opportunities to go back, but nobody ever claimed
a humanitarian catastrophe," he complained.
</P>
<P>
He also said there were 36 minorities in Serbia and the Serbs
have never expelled a non-Serb person from Serbia. But the
Albanians in Kosovo wanted a state of their own regardless of the
rights of other minorities, which was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
He said the major task and determination of the executive
council, the temporary government in Kosovo, was to see that
"everything is undertaken on the principles of equality and
non-discrimination of all nationalities."
</P>
<P>
"After successfully defeating the terrorists last month, we are
now getting down to reestablishing confidence and trust among the
population in Kosovo, and are very much ready to cooperate with
the ethnic Albanians in exercising their self-governance on
condition that the territorial integrity and sovereignty of the
country are not jeopardized," he said.
</P>
<P>
The de facto governor also criticized some countries which were
meddling in the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We are not a threat to peace. The real threat to peace are
those who trained and armed terrorists in Kosovo. We are attacked
and threatened by those terrorists," he said, referring to the
outlawed Albanian armed group, the so-called "Kosovo Liberation
Army" (KLA).
</P>
<P>
The KLA took up arms in March to fight for independence for
Kosovo, igniting the conflict which has forced thousands of people
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
"It is strange that Serbian police are prohibited from keeping
peace and order in their own state. It is strange that some
Western countries and NATO are keeping peace and order in another
country with missiles and air strikes. Can that really mean
peace?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
NATO ambassadors in Brussels agreed on Tuesday to suspend the
immediate threat of air strikes against Yugoslavia as Serbian
forces in Kosovo pulled out of the province in compliance with the
U.N. demands. But the alliance can still use force at any time if
necessary by extending the deadline indefinitely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
