<HEADLINE> India, France Begins Two-day Strategic Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- India and France began their
first round of strategic dialogue here on Wednesday, covering the
entire gamut of bilateral relations including the nuclear issue.
</P>
<P>
Principal Secretary to Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee Brajesh Mishra, who leads the Indian delegation, told the
press Wednesday following the first day meeting that he held
wide-ranging discussions with French President Jacques Chirac's
special envoy Gerard Errera, a diplomat in the French Embassy in
New Delhi, on areas including the issue of French cooperation in
the civilian nuclear energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue between the two countries is expected to subscribe
to the view point that the international order in the post-cold
war era should be a multipolar and not a unipolar one.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue comes at the time when talks between New Delhi and
Washington have bogged down and the Indian government undoubtedly
hoped that the Indo-French dialogue would push the United States
to be somewhat more accommodating.
</P>
<P>
Decision to initiate the dialogue was made during the Indian
Prime Minister's visit to Paris last month.
</P>
<P>
India has been following more or less French path on issues
such as nuclear disarmament, Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty,
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
