<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. Newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The North Atlantic Treaty Organization suspended its
immediate threat to attack Yugoslavia, concluding that President
Slobodan Milosevic was in "substantial compliance" with demands to
end his attacks on ethnic Albanians in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu postponed
ratification of the new Israeli-Palestinian accord by the cabinet
in an effort to placate right-wing critics. The delay was
condemned by Palestinian officials, who announced that they had
arrested suspects in the killing of a Jewish settler.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The global AIDS epidemic is forcing demographers to
dramatically scale back predictions for population growth over the
next century, as some African nations brace for losses as high as
a quarter of all adults, according to a United Nations study to be
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. and Turkish governments are stepping up pressure on
Western oil companies to support construction of a strategic but
controversial oil pipeline that would bring Caspian Sea crude to
Turkey's Mediterranean coast via a route avoiding both Russia and
Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Brazil's president Fernando Henrique Cardoso addressed the
nation to warn of tough times ahead. Details of his austerity
package, which will include budget reductions and tax increases
next year, are to be outlined Wednesday. The International
Monetary Fund is close to announcing a roughly 30 billion U.S.
dollars Brazil bailout as it tries to contain a global
emerging-market crisis.
</P>
<P>
-- A draft Russian economic plan was published in a Moscow
business paper, outlining vague steps the government is
considering to battle a financial crisis. Foreign investors
aren't likely to be reassured. Western banks resume
debt-restructuring talks Thursday. 
</P>
