<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Suspends Aid Program in Jamaica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Canada has suspended its
foreign-aid program in Jamaica, because the Jamaican government
has refused to explain the disappearance of nearly 18 million
Canadian dollars (11.7 million U.S. dollars) of development
assistance, Canada's National Post newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The dispute arose when Canadian auditors began looking into a
program in which Ottawa shipped commodities, such as fertilizers,
to Jamaica and the local government sold them to help
finance-aided projects.
</P>
<P>
Auditors at the Canadian International Development Agency
(CIDA) said when they visited Jamaica to try to track the money,
the government agency in charge of the program refused to hand
over relevant files and began shredding documents.
</P>
<P>
In a report to Ottawa in February, the auditors said they could
not determine how the money was spent.
</P>
<P>
Canada has asked Jamaica to investigate the implementation of
the program, which was set up to help finance infrastructure
programs, such as bridge-building.
</P>
<P>
But CIDA spokesman Robin Walsh said the Jamaican government had
not responded, and the Canadian government reacted by suspending
the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debate On Village Autonomy Vs. Party And Government Control (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A proposed amendment to the
Organic Law for Villagers' Committee submitted sparked an intense
debate today among Chinese lawmakers about villagers' autonomy and
Party and government control.
</P>
<P>
Most said that democratically-elected villagers' committees
should be independent of township governments and can be seen as
assistants but never subordinates, as amendment suggested.
</P>
<P>
Other members contended that without the power to control
villagers' committees, the local government could not accomplish
its many tasks like birth control and military conscription.
</P>
<P>
Shu Huaide, a member of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, said the existing rules are appropriate and
effective in guarding villagers' autonomy. If the committees were
subordinate, then township governments could appoint village heads
without acknowledging that they have to be elected by villagers
themselves.
</P>
<P>
The democratic election, decision-making, self-management and
supervision, which are the goal of this piece of legislation,
would then be impossible, he said.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Jiang Shusheng countered by saying that if democracy
is overdone, there will be too many difficulties, and with no
leadership for villagers committees, local governments might not
have enough to fulfill birth control and military quotas.
</P>
<P>
Huang Changxi, Sui Yongju and Li Meng said that villagers
committees, as assistants of the local government, must actively
support the government in these tasks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
