<HEADLINE> Foreign Direct Investment in Pak down by 79 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 Dollars
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Inflow of direct foreign
investment into Pakistan has shrunk by 79 million U.S. dollars in
July and August this year, according to figures released Wednesday
by the Board of Investment (BOI).
</P>
<P>
Pakistan attracted a total of 74.4 million foreign direct
investment in July and August, the first two months of the current
fiscal year, while in the similar period last fiscal year, the
foreign direct investment stood at 153.2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The foreign direct investment drifted away from the power
sector in July to August this fiscal year by ending at 30.6
million dollars in comparison with 74 million in the same period
last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures by BOI, cement, tourism and
petro-chemical and refining sectors did not receive foreign direct
investment in July and August.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. investment in Pakistan during the two months was 37
million dollars, while investment from the U.K. was 11 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The foreign investors are closely watching the quarrel between
the government and Independent Power producers on tariff and once
it is settled they will be able to take fresh positions on
investment in Pakistan, the BOI said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
