<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Congo (K) Crisis Talks Make No </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The just concluded ministerial
meeting held in Zambian capital Lusaka has made no breakthrough
on the three-month long crisis in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) despite a draft ceasefire agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka meeting is no doubt the largest high-level
gathering of its kind called by African countries in an effort to
bring a speedy and peaceful solution to the complicated situation
in the vast central African country since the crisis broke out in
early August.
</P>
<P>
It attracted more than 130 delegates including foreign and
defense ministers from at least 14 African countries as well as
senior officials from the United Nations, the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) and the Southern African Development
Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
What is noticeable is that all the key players directly or
indirectly involved in the Congo (K) crisis such as Zimbabwe,
Namibia, Angola, Rwanda, Uganda, Burundi and the DRC were present
at the meeting, a case which has never happened in the
mini-summit meetings in Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe or in Pretoria
and Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting which focused on issues relating to
the cessation of hostilities in the DRC, the implementation of a
ceasefire and withdrawal of foreign forces, adopted a draft
ceasefire agreement and a mechanism for its implementation and
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
The participants also agreed at the talks to establish a
mechanism for the involvement of the rebels, who came to Lusaka
but was denied access to the meeting, in working out the
modalities for the implementation of the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
However, the meeting, which was described as "very important"
and "successful" by SADC Executive Secretary Kaire Mbende, has
not made any breakthrough on the DRC crisis since the proposed
ceasefire is far from being a "practical" accord to implement due
to lack of concrete measures.
</P>
<P>
Some key players still hold their own previous stands and
their major differences on the withdrawal of foreign forces and
cessation of hostilities remain to be ironed out.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing Tuesday afternoon during the intervals of
the meeting, Congolese Foreign Minister Jean Charles Okoto
stressed his government only deals with Rwanda and Uganda instead
of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
He strongly urged the two countries which have been accused by
Kinshasa of invasion and of backing the rebels to withdraw their
troops from Congo (K) immediately, saying the troops from Rwanda
and Uganda should be treated differently from those of Kinshasa's
allies, Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Congo (K) Crisis Talks Make No </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But Bizima Karaha, President Laurent Kabila's former foreign
minister who led the rebel delegation, later told reporters that
unless the Congolese government sits down and talks with the
rebels there will be no solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Karaha also noted that "the Congolese problem can only be
resolved by the Congolese people themselves".
</P>
<P>
While Rwanda again firmly denied sending troops to the former
Zaire, Uganda acknowl its deployment of troops in the
DRC and tried to justify its military presence there.
</P>
<P>
A statement released at the end of the ministerial meeting by
Ugandan Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Amama Mbabazi
declared Uganda has security interests in eastern Congo (K) and
it sent troops to fight against those Ugandan Hutu-rebels who
established bases there to topple Kampala's current government.
It also insisted that all the foreign forces should leave the
country.
</P>
<P>
"Our view is that all foreign troops should leave the DRC. The
withdrawal should be done after a ceasefire and when neutral
multi-national forces have taken up positions in the DRC to
supervise strict observance of the ceasefire and ensure security
of the neighboring countries," Mbabazi said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day closed-door meeting, the atmosphere was tense
from the very beginning to the end. Those countries involved in
the crisis were obviously divided into two camps and the meeting
almost came to an failure before Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba, who was earlier mandated by African leaders to mediate
the Congo (K) crisis, managed to persuade Rwandan and Ugandan
delegations which had backed out during consultations Monday
evening to return to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here observed that the Lusaka meeting made
no more progress than the pervious talks of such nature. They
said no "meaningful" solutions could be found until the rebels
who control most part of the eastern Congo (K) were directly
involved in working out a "practical" and "concrete" ceasefire
and all the key players reached a consensus on the withdrawal of
foreign troops.
</P>
<P>
They also believed that the crisis, which has drawn in more
and more African countries, tended to escalate and peace and
stability of the African continent, particularly in the Great
Lakes region, would be threatened and a "disaster" for the
African people, as a result, is "unavoidable".
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they said the way for the African leaders to find a
practical solution to the Congo (K) crisis is still long and more
concerted efforts should be made in order to narrow the existing
major differences of the key players as soon as possible and pave
the way for restoring peace in the country in an "African way."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
