<HEADLINE> Georgian Songs, Dances Thrill HK Audience in Asian Arts Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The audience in the Hong Kong
Cultural Center's Grand Theater were thrilled by the graceful
dances of Georgian woman and courage of their male counterparts as
Georgian artists began for the first time in Hong Kong a two-day
performance program on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With sparks flash amidst dagger and sword strikes, the warrior
dancers displayed a unique culture of the former Soviet Union
republic in the Caucasus. "It is part of the country's tradition
featuring involvement in numerous wars in the history," explained
soloist Givi Shanidze, who is the founder and artist director of
the visiting Kolkheti Ensemble.
</P>
<P>
In the past 18 years since its founding, the prize-winning song
and dance troupe has visited more than 30 countries and regions in
Asia, Europe and Americas.
</P>
<P>
The performance given by Kolkheti is part of the program for
the on-going 17th Festival of Asian Arts here, which goes through
mid-November.
</P>
<P>
"Although we'd just arrived here Monday afternoon, Hong Kong
has given us a very good and positive impression," said Teimuraz
Kobakhidze, the choreographer of the Kolkheti Song and Dance
Company.
</P>
<P>
"We have a very strong aspiration to visit China sometime in
the future, as we all know China is famed for its long history and
cultural heritage," said English-speaking Nino Lazishvili, the
troupe's leading female dancer. She was brought into a dancing
career five years ago by her mother, a famed dancer in a national
troupe.
</P>
<P>
"Dancing is very important in our country. It's part of our
life," she added.
</P>
<P>
Among the limelights of the opening-day program on Wednesday
were folk songs, Song of Labor, Song of the Riders, Dance with
Flute Music and Danced Poem of Love.
</P>
<P>
With an ancient history, Georgia is well-known for its original
and unique culture. The Georgians have created through past
centuries unique arts including music, choreography, architecture,
folklore and decoration.
</P>
<P>
The Georgians have maintained their own spoken and written
language, and architecture, religion and musical culture. The
Georgian music features a unique polyphony, which follows rules
very different from those of European polyphonic choral music,
according to Shanidze.
</P>
<P>
In modern Georgia, however, many of the original folk songs are
sung only as performance, instead of usually being part of the
daily life. The Kolkheti is among various local organizations and
individual artists devoted in preserving Georgian folk music, he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
