<HEADLINE> Sea Level In India's Southern Coast Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Several locations along
India's southern coast are slowly rising from the sea as the
sea-level is falling at a rate of about one millimeter per year,
according to an Indian scientific journal.
</P>
<P>
Several coastal regions in the southern Karnataka state are
moving up at a rate ranging from 0.65 to 1.3 mm per year, shows a
recent study carried out by K. R. Subrahmanya from Jawaharlal
Nehru Center for Advanced scientific Research (JNCASR) in
Bangalore, 2060 kilometers south of here.
</P>
<P>
An increase in the rate of sedimentation along the coastal line
has also been found, JNCASR scientists said in the latest edition
of Current Science.
</P>
<P>
In a region named Baindur, the land has been uplifted by four
to six meters in about 6400 years at a rate of 0.63 to 0.94 mm per
year, the Journal said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
