<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Demining Forum Closed in Phnom Penh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Three-day International
Forum on Demining and Victim Assistance is closed here Wednesday,
promoting the exchanges on experiences and information in
demining.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 participants from about 50 countries attended the
forum, most of them are the most mine-affected countries.
</P>
<P>
Ieng Mouly, chairman of the Cambodian Mine Action Center
(CMAC), said at the closing meeting that the forum was fruitful.
</P>
<P>
"This forum is to open the opportunity for donor countries to
see the facts in mine-affected countries like Cambodia, and a
chance for mine-affected countries coming from all of the world to
share experiences," Ieng Mouly said.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the forum is "Toward Zero Victims Based on
Ownership and Partnership".
</P>
<P>
Cambodia remains one of the most heavily mined countries in the
world. It is estimated there are still 4 to 6 million landmines in
Cambodia soil. Today Cambodia continues to pay a heavy price. In
1998, the country suffers between 150 and 200 casualties a month
from mines and unexploded ordnance.
</P>
<P>
With the help of donor countries and international
organizations, Cambodia has made a great efforts to demine and
assist the victims.
</P>
<P>
To date, CMAC has cleared 152 minefields, destroyed about
40,000 anti-personnel mines, more than 900 anti-tank mines and
nearly 50,000 pieces of unexploded ordnance.
</P>
<P>
Sam Sitha, director general of CMAC, told the reporters: "We
guarantee that within 30 years, landmines will be removed from
Cambodia if such activities are continued."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
