<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh-India Border Coordination Conference Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A three-day-long Bangladesh-India
border coordination conference ended in Dhaka Wednesday with a
decision made by the two sides to complete the demarcation of the
"disputed" portion of their common boundary before the onset of
the next monsoon, an official press release said.
</P>
<P>
Top officials of the border security forces of the two
countries agreed that the 6.5 kilometer-long un-demarcated land
boundary would be properly marked before May next year, the
release stated.
</P>
<P>
Major General Azizur Rahman, director general of the Bangladesh
Rifles, led a 20-member team at the conference, while Sree EN
Rammohan, director general of the Indian Border Security Forces,
led the 10-member visiting team.
</P>
<P>
The team leaders of the two countries signed a joint record
after the conclusion of the session.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, various cross border problems like
smuggling of arms, narcotics and other commodities and border
demarcation, repair and maintenance of demarcated pillars were
discussed, it stated, adding that trafficking of women and
children and matters of mutual interest also came up for
discussion.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to cooperate with each other in
adopting effective measures to curb cross border crimes, it added.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
