<HEADLINE> Four Detainees at U.N. Tribunal End Hunger Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Four suspects detained
at the United Nations tribunal for 1994 Rwanda genocide have
ended their hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
Kingsley Moghalu, spokesman for the U. N. International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) in Tanzania's northern town
of Arusha, said that the four detainees resumed eating and
drinking Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"They asked for their meal, normal food, and were supplied,"
Moghalu said in a telephone interview with Xinhua Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But the ICTR spokesman declined to brief the latest
development in the detention facilities on the outskirts of
Arusha where 33 detainees are held awaiting for their trial or
appeal for their roles in the genocide.
</P>
<P>
The 25 detainees embarked on the hunger strike Monday in
collaboration with former Rwandan mayor Jean-Paul Akayesu who had
been on hunger strike since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Arusha said that some other detainees were seen
secretly taking biscuits and juices in their facilities.
</P>
<P>
Akayesu has been convicted of genocide and sentenced to a life
imprisonment by the ICTR earlier this month for his role in
Rwanda's 1994 massacre.
</P>
<P>
In a signed letter to the Tribunal, the detainees protested
alleged denial of their human rights in the assignment of the
lawyers by the ICTR Registry.
</P>
<P>
However, Registrar Agwu Okali fired back Tuesday by saying in
a news release that the assignment of counsel is his
responsibility under the tribunal's rules.
</P>
<P>
"Defense lawyers are assigned to detainees who can not afford
the costs of hiring their own lawyer in order to ensure respect
for the right of the accused to a fair trial," Okali said. "This
responsibility is acknowledged by the detainees in their letter."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
