<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clan Leaders Urged to Stop Hostilities in Niger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Delta State
administrator has appealed to leaders of the warring Ijaw and
Itsekiri communities in Niger Delta region to order their youths
to stop all hostilities, This Day newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Administrator Walter Faghebo as saying
Tuesday that the state government vowed to deal with anyone who
threatens peace and order in oil town of Warri and its environs
as 500 soldiers police the town to forestall renewed fighting.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued Monday night at the end of a peace meeting
to solve Warri crisis in Asaba, capital of Delta State, called
for immediate halt to current hostilities between Ijaws and
Itsekiris.
</P>
<P>
The ten-point communique said that the Itsekiris had agreed to
the creation of a separate local government for the Ijaws and a
powerful delegation led by the Delta State administrator would be
sent to Nigerian capital Abuja to seek lasting solution to the
Warri crisis.
</P>
<P>
The two ethnic groups have been engaged in violent conflicts
since 1996 over the relocation of Warri South Local Government
from Ogbe-Ijoh, an Ijaw settlement, to Ogidegben, an Itsekiri
settlement.
</P>
<P>
The latest conflict started 11 days ago as some Ijaw youths
were alleged to have attacked an Itsekiri funeral procession.
</P>
<P>
The communique noted that unemployment is a major secondary
cause of the crisis, therefore, calling on the Nigerian federal
government, oil companies operating in Niger Delta area and the
private sector to provide employment opportunities for the
youths.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the peace meeting agreed that all oil
transmission stations occupied by the rampaging Ijaw youths
should be vacated while all waterways blocked should be cleared
and made safe for a free and uninterrupted passage.
</P>
<P>
Although Ijaws and Itsekiris agreed to immediate halt to
hostilities, both communities insisted on certain conditions
being met before a lasting peace could be achieved in Warri and
its environs, according to Wednesday's The Guardian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Fregene, spokesman of the Itsekiri, said that "this
meeting did not achieve more than appealing to the two sides to
lay down their arms."
</P>
<P>
He noted that "we cannot talk of peace when the Itsekiris are
still rendered homeless, when the Itsekiri communities are still
being burnt down, when the Ijaws are still armed." 
</P>
</TEXT>
