<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Gets Tough on Gangs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The South African
parliament has intensified the campaign against gang bosses by
stiffening punishment and modifying laws concerning gang crimes.
</P>
<P>
The parliament's justice committee Tuesday put forward a
revised bill which raises the maximum fine and jail term for
racketeering from 10 million Rand (1.75 million U.S. Dollars) to
one billion Rand (175 million Dollars) and from 30 years to life
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
"Now we can really nail these buggers," committee chairman
Johnny de Lange said in a debate on the Prevention of Organized
Crime Bill, which is expected to set in place the necessary legal
steps "to deal with the tyranny of organized crime," Business
Paper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the reason for increasing the fine -- at one
billion Rand, the highest in South Africa's legal history -- was
the huge sums of money involved in organized crime.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the maximum sentence to life was because gang
bosses could often be convicted only on racketeering charges
while their gangs were responsible for extremely serious
offenses, such as murder.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for civil and criminal forfeiture of assets.
In the case of civil forfeiture, any asset involved in a crime or
proceeds of a crime can be confiscated by the state, even though
there has been no conviction.
</P>
<P>
To make it easier for the state to convict a gangster, the
definition of racketeering offenses was strengthened through the
de-linking and broadening of certain clauses.
</P>
<P>
The committee is scheduled to conclude its work this week, in
time for the bill to be put to the National Assembly for adoption
at the end of next week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
