<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Stop Foreign Exchange Swapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- China has decided to stop the
business of foreign exchange swapping among overseas-funded
enterprises as of December 1.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange settlementments by related enterprises
will be conducted through banks, according to a circular jointly
issued today by the People's Bank of China and the State
Administration of Foreign Exchange.
</P>
<P>
This move aims to unify the Chinese foreign exchange markets,
says the circular, and it is expected to cut down procedures for
foreign-funded enterprises to sell or purchase foreign currency
and accelerate capital turnover.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign exchange swapping business started in 1980 and
has played an important role in helping Chinese and overseas-funded
enterprises exchange their surplus and deficiency in
foreign currency. Yet since 1996, when buying and selling foreign
currency through banks became available to overseas-funded
businesses, foreign exchange trade in the country has been handled
mostly through the banking system.
</P>
<P>
The banks' foreign exchange settlement system is basically
mature and can now meet the business demands of institutions and
enterprises, the circular says.
</P>
<P>
The circular also detailed measures for transforming or closing
foreign exchange swapping centers throughout the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
