<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special Courts Protect Women From Domestic Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province
has established 87 courts to deal with cases involving the
violation of women's rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
"The largest number of cases these courts receive concern
domestic violence," said Wang Shirong, vice president of the
Shanxi Higher People's Court. Wang is one of the founders of the
first court of this kind in China, established in Shanxi in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Domestic violence occurs most frequently in underdeveloped
provinces such as Shanxi, Wang pointed out, and women victims
could find little legal protection because many cases were not
considered serious enough for regular courts.
</P>
<P>
"With these special courts, women are able to go through legal
procedures to settle cases of domestic violence," she said.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the special courts are playing a very important
role in protecting women's rights and interests and helping them
learn to protect themselves with legal means.
</P>
<P>
Following Shanxi's example, Hebei, Jiangsu, Liaoning, Henan and
Shaanxi provinces have also established such courts for women.
</P>
<P>
About 8 percent of Chinese women have suffered at least once
from domestic violence, and nearly 1 percent have been victims of
frequent violence from family members, according to a recent
survey by the All-China Women's Federation.
</P>
<P>
Domestic violence against women has to be controlled with
comprehensive social efforts, said Li Hui, a member of the Chinese
Women Judges Association. She said that the concept of domestic
violence has to been defined more clearly in relevant laws, and
that judges should be trained to deal with such cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
