<HEADLINE> Boycott of States Moving Embassies to Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Council of
Mosques under the Muslim World League has called for Arab and
Islamic boycott of states which move their embassies in Israel
from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of its 18th session held in Mecca, Saudi
Arabia Tuesday night, the council asserted that "Jerusalem was an
Arab and Islamic capital which cannot be abandoned and should be
reserved along with the Aqsa Mosque," the Kuwait News Agency
(Kuna) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israel, which captured the eastern sector of Jerusalem from
Jordan in 1967, claims all of city as its eternal capital, while
Palestinians demand control of the Arab section and want to make
it the capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. resolution in 1947, Jerusalem, the seat for
Islamic, Jewish and Christian religions, is under international
mandate.
</P>
<P>
But in 1950, Israel removed its capital to Jerusalem and in
1980 declared it as its united and eternal capital.
</P>
<P>
The unilateral moves have been opposed by the international
community and the Islamic world. Almost all countries that have
diplomatic relations with Israel have refused to move their
embassies from Tel aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The council also reiterated its keenness and commitment to
legislative rights of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
It recommended to closely follow up Israeli activities and
attempts against Islamic religious symbols in Palestine and
elsewhere in the world, Kuna said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction of Dhaka Embankment to Start Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The construction of a
38-kilometer-long Dhaka Flood Control-cum-Eastern Bypass
Multipurpose Project involving an estimated cost of 30 billion
taka (619 million U.S. dollars) is expected to start next month, a
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the Japanese government had shown interest
in providing the necessary fund for the implementation of the
project, a competent source from the Ministry of Water Resources
was quoted by The Bangladesh Observer as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Japan International Cooperative Agency completed
the feasibility study of the embankment with the financial
assistance from the Japanese government, while the World Bank
completed the feasibility study of the roads, sluice gates,
culverts and bridges of the project, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government will spend 10 billion taka (206
million dollars) from its own resources for the acquisition of
lands and earth work of the embankment.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of the highest-level Steering Committee headed by the
prime minister will finalize the date for launching the project,
and three committees have been formed to implement the project, he
added.
</P>
<P>
After the necessary scrutiny, the Planning Commission will send
the project concept paper to the Steering Committee to start the
work in November.
</P>
<P>
This is the second phase of the whole project, and the first
phase of the Dhaka City Flood Protection Embankment is yet to be
completed.
</P>
<P>
The work of the first phase began in November 1992 with an
estimated cost of 5.37 billion taka (111 million dollars) provided
by the Asian Development Bank, and 4 billion taka (83 million
dollars) has already been spent on the first phase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
