<HEADLINE> More Than 4,000 Ugandan Soldiers Deployed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has deployed a total of
more than 4,000 troops in the eastern part of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC), Wednesday's Monitor paper reported.
</P>
<P>
There are nearly 200,000 armed men on the ground facing off on
both sides, it said.
</P>
<P>
The figure is reported to have been got from independent and
diplomatic sources because many governments continue to deny that
their troops are involved in the three-month-long conflict.
</P>
<P>
When contacted for confirmation, the information office of the
defense ministry told Xinhua Wednesday morning that they are not
in a position to comment on that.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni told a press conference last week
that Uganda has more than two battalions of soldiers in eastern
DRC and promised not to send reinforcements there unless the
situation worsens.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Zimbabwe has 3,000 to 5,000 soldiers
in the DRC while Angola and Namibia deploy 4,000 and 300 soldiers
there respectively.
</P>
<P>
There are 60,000 Tutsi rebels fighting against some 60,000
Kabila ground forces, it was reported.
</P>
<P>
Growing concerns are not gripping more and more countries in
the region and even in the continent with rapid widening of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan called for an immediate
withdrawal of foreign troops from the DRC and the U.S. government
sent a special envoy to the Great Lakes Region to persuade the
key players in the conflict to stop hostilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
