<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Sign on SADC Trade Pacts: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has pledged
to the signing of Southern African Development Community (SADC)
trade protocols, according to the South African trade minister.
</P>
<P>
The South African government is possibly to sign the protocols
next year, thus paving the way for a free trade area in the
region, Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin said Tuesday at a
press briefing during a regional business conference with the
participation of representatives from SADC members.
</P>
<P>
The Sowetan daily Wednesday quoted Erwin as saying that
regional integration was not an option but an imperative.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa cannot adapt to globalization on its own," he
said. "We have to move in unison with SADC members over time."
</P>
<P>
The South African minister noted that a number of trade and
joint initiatives with other SADC members were in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
SADC Deputy Secretary-General Prega Ramsamy, who attended the
conference, said there were currently 472 projects under way in
the region which are valued at 60 million Rand (about 10 million
U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
So far, there were four countries of 14 SADC member states,
Botswana, Mauritius, Tanzania and Zimbabwe, who signed SADC trade
protocols, which provide for the creation of a SADC free trade
area within eight years.
</P>
<P>
According to Ramsamy, at present more than 70 percent of SADC
trade is taking place at tariffs below 10 percent, and by the end
of 1999 the SADC can achieve a partial free trade area covering
some 70 to 80 percent of internal SADC trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
