<HEADLINE> Mozambican Aluminum Workers Abandon Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Workers of the Mozambican
Aluminum Company (MOZAL) have decided to abandon strikes because
they are aware of the the importance of the on-going MOZAL
project.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Noticias newspaper quoted the company's trade
union leader Jeremisa Timana as saying that the workers have done
so because they are aware of the importance of the MOZAL project
and the significance of its completion in time.
</P>
<P>
The workers went on a three-day strike in late September for
pay increment. Just a few days ago, they threatened to strike
again.
</P>
<P>
MOZAL lost some one million U.S. Dollars each day during their
strikes.
</P>
<P>
Though abandoning strikes, MOZAL workers also asked the
national trade union of civil construction, timber industry and
mines to negotiate with the management of the project on a
mechanism of sustainably raising pays for the workers, said
Timana.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican Labor Ministry decided to give a 10 percent pay
raise to the MOZAL workers last week, thus avoiding another
strike.
</P>
<P>
Timana said the management had acknowledged that there were
mistakes at the early phase of the project.
</P>
<P>
Now, it is different, he said, adding that the labor and the
management no longer push responsibilities upon the other.
</P>
<P>
The 1.2-billion-U.S. Dollar project started in mid this year
is the biggest one in recent years in the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
The funds came from various companies of Mozambique, South
Africa, the United Kingdom and Japan. The ores will come from
Australia and MOZAL products will go to Asian and European
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
