<HEADLINE> Myanmar Allows More NLD Members to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar Authorities have
allowed 49 members of the National League for Democracy (NLD) to
go home during these three days starting Monday after "view
exchanges" with them, according to an official information sheet
issued here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of the NLD members who were allowed to return home
after "housing" them for several weeks at the state guest houses
went to 73 since September 14.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the NLD Monday, a total of
987 of its party members including 200 parliament
representatives-elect and 787 party organizers have been detained
by the authorities since May 27 this year.
</P>
<P>
The NLD has denied that the authorities had exchanged views
with its detained members, saying that they were, in fact,
"interrogated."
</P>
<P>
On September 16, the NLD formed a 10-member committee
representing the parliament elected in the 1990 multi-party
general election and set up a People's Parliament after its
deadline for the parliament to be convened was ignored by the
government.
</P>
<P>
After the NLD's formation of the People's Parliament, the
government has organized a series of mass rallies in different
states and divisions, denouncing the NLD's move.
</P>
<P>
The NLD said in a letter to the chairman of the Myanmar State
Peace and Development Council (SPDC) on October 13 that the
authorities are "illegally" using people from all walks of life
who are under "pressure" for the expression of "the people's
desire," creating further political confusion.
</P>
<P>
The NLD also stressed that it reserves the right to organize
similar mass rallies to present facts on the current situation in
Myanmar as it is a legal political party.
</P>
<P>
Assistant United Nations (U.N.) Secretary General Alvaro de
Soto, special envoy of the U.N. secretary general, arrived here
Tuesday on his second four-day trip to Myanmar this year to look
into the current political situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Alvaro is expected to meet Lieutenant General Khin Nyunt, first
secretary of the SPDC, as well as Aung San Suu Kyi, general
secretary of the opposition NLD, during his trip.
</P>
<P>
The authorities' recent allowance of a large number of the NLD
members to return home coincides with Alvaro's visit, observers
here believed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
