<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Court Rejects Anwar's Habeas Corpus Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's High Court
Wednesday rejected an application for habeas corpus for the
release of former deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim who is now
at remand in a prison near here.
</P>
<P>
Justice Abdul Wahab Patail ruled there was no merit in pursuing
the application as Anwar is no longer under the Internal Security
Act (ISA) detention.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who was detained under the ISA on September 20 following
street protests by his supporters, was released unconditionally on
October 14 and transferred immediately to the Sungai Buloh prison
for remand.
</P>
<P>
The judge made the decision after hearing submissions from
counsel Sulaiman Abdullah, one of Anwar's eight lawyers, and
Senior Federal Counsel Kamaludin Mohamed Said.
</P>
<P>
He said that since Anwar was currently held under remand at the
Sungai Buloh prison by an order of the High Court pending his
trial, it would be wholly wrong, in law and principle, for him to
contest that order.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's trial on four corruption charges is due to start
Monday. He is also facing another corruption charge and five
counts of unnatural sex acts.
</P>
<P>
the judge said whatever grievance Anwar might have, political
or otherwise, is clearly not the subject of a habeas corpus
application. The applicant's proper avenue of redress is by way of
an appeal, and not by this collateral application.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was sacked as deputy prime minister and finance minister
on September 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
