<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
stronger Wednesday as quarterly inflation figures reinforced
market opinion that a Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) interest
rate cut was imminent.
</P>
<P>
In another quiet trading day, the local currency ended at 61.70
U.S. cents, up from its close in local trade Tuesday of 61.50 U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
The currency traded between 61.55 U.S. cents and 61.85 U.S.
cents during the session.
</P>
<P>
Australian Bureau of Statistics data, released here Wednesday,
showed the consumer price index (CPI) rose 0.2 percent for the
September quarter for a rise of 1.3 percent in the year.
</P>
<P>
The annual figure came in below the RBA's targeted range of two
to three percent.
</P>
<P>
Kevin Tuckey, foreign exchange dealer with Macquarie Bank, said
the inflation figures did not stand in the way of a rate cut,
which could come at any time.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have been talking about possible rate cuts by RBA,
Australia's central bank, ever since the United State's Federal
Reserve lowered its interest rates earlier this month in a bid to
boost U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly the CPI figures today emphasized that we can expect
it (a rate cut) anytime from now onwards," Tuckey said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 72.87 Japanese yen from 73.35
yen and 1.0194 German marks from 1.0216 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
