<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Commodity Fair Welcomes Private Businesses, Says Trade Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 28 (Xinhua) -- China will encourage more
private enterprises to participate in the biannual Guangzhou
Commodity Fair held in this capital of south China's Guangdong
Province, a senior foreign trade official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that Chinese private enterprises will fully use
this 'window' to expand their influence and march toward the
world," said Sun Zhenyu, vice-minister of foreign trade and
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation announced that private enterprises will be granted the
right of direct import and export as of January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that with the increased status of private firms in
the national economy, it is inevitable that more room be made for
their development.
</P>
<P>
Chinese private enterprises, beginning with the service sector,
has rapidly expanded into almost every part of the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
According to state statistics, China has nearly 30 million
private and individual businesses employing some 70 million people.
</P>
<P>
However, private enterprises still must go through state-owned
foreign trade entities to conduct import and export business, and
most of their products are displayed at the commodity fair under
the names of their agent companies.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Shuakang Co Ltd. is the only private enterprise in the
home electric appliance hall of the ongoing 84th commodity fair.
</P>
<P>
A manager of the company said that exporting through agents,
his company was unable to use its own brand and get feed back,
which is detrimental to upgrading products.
</P>
<P>
Without the right of export, private enterprises must combat
each other in the domestic market, he said, adding that they will
go far in the world market if the restriction is lifted.
</P>
<P>
Liu Wei, a manager with a private company in east China's
Shandong Province, said that better treatment has been given to
private enterprises at this fair, and his company was able to get
three booths this time, in contrast to the half-booth at previous
fairs.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Sun Weihua, general manager of the Ningbo Fuda IMP &AMP;
EXP Co., Ltd. said that easing control of import and export may
intensify competition among enterprises, therefore the control
should be lifted, step by step.
</P>
<P>
But such competition is, at the same time, a good thing, as it
will help increase the reputation of Chinese enterprises and their
products on the international market, Sun added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
