<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior IMF Official Optimistic About Asian Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) told a press conference here
Wednesday that the downturn in a number of crisis economies in
Asia will bottom out in the first half of next year.
</P>
<P>
Flemming Larsen, who has been serving as deputy director of
research at the IMF since 1992 and holding senior responsibility
for the IMF's flagship publication of the World Economic Outlook,
said when answering questions that he expects the economic
downturn in Thailand and South Korea will bottom out in the second
quarter of next year and the recovery to be on the way by the
second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
On Hong Kong and Singapore, Larsen said given their dependence
on what happens in the region, it is impossible to make assumption
on what will happen, citing what happens in China is very
important for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
But Larsen underlined there is chance that the economy in Hong
Kong will turn around early next year.
</P>
<P>
The deputy director noted a number of favorable developments
have been seen since the beginning of October and these are the
kind of developments and positive actions that are helping to
reduce the risk that the crisis is going to get even worse.
</P>
<P>
"In Asia we have seen very welcome improvement in market
confidence, stabilization in financial market and significant
easing of monetary (situation) in the countries most affected by
the crisis," he said
</P>
<P>
Citing Japan's commitment to addressing the problem of bank
system he billed it as "encouraging news", saying it is not only
crucial for Japan's recovery but also crucial to the recovery of
the entire region.
</P>
<P>
Larsen underlined that the industrialized countries have made
"helpful decisions" to begin "to ease monetary conditions in order
to contract what many have termed global critical crunch."
</P>
<P>
Larsen stressed that people need to be prepared to receive
further bad news in some cases in terms of the performance of weak
economies.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is too soon to conclude that the downturn in the
Asian crisis economies have bottomed out," he noted
</P>
<P>
The picture on the world economy drawn by Larsen now is
brighter than in the advance copy of the World Economic Outlook
completed in September.
</P>
<P>
The assumptions and analysis in the book's preface are
"international economic and financial conditions have been
deteriorated considerably in recent months as recessions have
deepened in many Asian emerging market economies and Japan, and as
Russia' financial crisis has raised the specter of default.
Negative spillovers have been felt in world stock markets,
emerging market interest spreads, acute pressures on several
currencies and further drops in already weak commodity prices."
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
