<HEADLINE> Separate Schools for Rebel Child Members in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government will
provide separate schools with hostel facilities for the Tamil
rebel child members who surrendered to government troops,
according to a report of the official evening news paper the
Observer Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by President Chandrika Kumaratunga at a
discussion with the Presidential Task Force Committee and
ambassador of several countries here at the Presidential
Secretariat recently, the Observer said.
</P>
<P>
This decision was taken because sending the children to normal
schools could pose a threat to their lives.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has allowed the parents of those who
surrendered to visit them, they are reluctant to do so because of
the threat from the Tamil rebels, the paper quoted Kumaratunga as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a 15-year war for a
separate state in the country since 1983. 
</P>
