<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review: Correct Policies Enable Bottoming Out of Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- By the end of the third
quarter, China's gross domestic product (GDP) had registered a
growth of 7.2 percent, a considerable recovery from the 7 percent
mid-year growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Official sources predict that the GDP will realize a further
rise in the last quarter, and that China's 8 percent GDP growth
target for the whole year is still attainable.
</P>
<P>
Many noted economists in Beijing hold the view that, while
neighboring countries are suffering from negative growth due to
the serious consequences of the Asian financial crisis, China's
economy remains stable, and has shown signs of bottoming out in
the second half of this year. This has been attributed mainly to
the correct macroeconomic policies implemented by China this year.
</P>
<P>
In line with the economic growth target and current economic
conditions, the Chinese government formulated a series of policies
for expanding investment and domestic demand and encouraging
export, which have been earnestly carried out throughout the
country since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
In January, the central bank lifted the ceiling on commercial
bank loans, enabling the banks to increase loans. By the end of
September, the outstanding amount of loans by financial
institutions exceeded 8.26 trillion yuan, up 16 percent from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The fact that a large part of the increased loans are medium-
and long-term loans indicates that the country's macroeconomic
policies of increasing infrastructure investment and expanding
domestic demand through credit are becoming apparent.
</P>
<P>
The central bank lowered interest rates for deposit and loans
twice earlier this year, and appropriately increased the money
supply. By the end of September the outstanding amount of money
in circulation and broad money rose 11.7 percent and 16 percent,
respectively, from the same 1997 period. Adjusting for price
factors, the actual growth of the money supply is 3 percentage
points higher.
</P>
<P>
In September, the Ministry of Finance announced the issuance of
100 billion yuan (12 billion US dollars) in special treasury
bonds, revenues from which will be used for infrastructure
construction. This step was taken to stimulate individual
consumption and enterprise investment and indirectly increase
demand in society at large.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
