<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review: Correct Policies Enable Bottoming Out of Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Commercial banks have also allocated more than 100 billion yuan
to facilitate this move. Economists believe that this 200 billion
yuan total will contribute 2 percentage points to GDP growth.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Chinese government has been rectifying various
charges to ease the burden on enterprises so that can retain more
working capital. At the same time, new policies have been issued
to increase export tax rebates for some industries and accelerate
the proceeding of tax rebates for export goods in an effort to
support export growth.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, after a slow period, these financial and
fiscal policies have gradually become effective. Industrial
production has had faster growth, with industrial added value up
8.6 percent in the third quarter from the same period last year,
in September this figure reaching 10.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Accelerated investment in fixed assets became a major
economic-growth factor. In the first nine months the amount of
investment in fixed assets reached 1.09 trillion yuan, up 20
percent from the same period last year, with most of the money put
into basic industries and new, high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
Domestic market sales have been gradually recovering. In the
third quarter the sales volume of consumer goods rose seven
percent from the same quarter last year, one percentage point
higher than the growth in the first half of this year; foreign
trade continued to grow, with a trade surplus of 35.3 billion
U.S. dollars in the first nine months; while foreign direct
investment reached 31.4 billion U.S. dollars, equaling that of the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Financial Institute under the State Council's
Development and Research Center, Wei Jia'ning , said, "Facing
complicated international and domestic economic conditions,
China's economy still maintained a steady and fast growth, this in
itself is a great success."
</P>
<P>
When analyzing general economic situation, a group of noted
economists from the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences regarded
the third quarter of this year as a turning point for China's
economy, with the GDP beginning to bottom out and a new growth
period approaching.
</P>
<P>
Liu Wei, vice-president of the Institute of Economics at
Beijing University, said China's economy will go on improving next
year, and the GDP growth is expected to exceed this year's 8
percent goal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
