<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Can Pay Off Foreign Debts in Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, the first of China's
five special economic zones, will pay off 6.25 billion
U.S. dollars of its foreign debt, dispelling doubts about its
debt-paying ability.
</P>
<P>
Of the 6.25 billion dollars, 5.3 billion was borrowed by
overseas-funded businesses, and of the city's total debt, only
25.6 percent is short-term debt, said Li Zibin, the mayor of
Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The mayor said that Shenzhen will pay off over 1.9 billion
dollars of debt due this year and has already paid 1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
"Shenzhen can definitely pay off its debt," said Li, "we won't
delay by even one day."
</P>
<P>
He also said Shenzhen will not only pay off its debts in time,
but will not need to borrow much from foreigners in the
foreseeable future because Shenzhen has ample funds.
</P>
<P>
To show how strong Shenzhen's economy is, the mayor said that
despite the harm done by the southeast Asian financial crisis, the
Shenzhen economy has been growing at a fast, continuous and
healthy pace.
</P>
<P>
During the first nine months of this year, Shenzhen completed a
GDP of 29.46 billion yuan, representing a rise of 14.3 percent
over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The mayor stressed that in China's ongoing reform and opening
up process, Shenzhen's status and function will not weaken, but
grow stronger.
</P>
<P>
"It will continue to function as the experimental ground in
China's transition to the socialist market economy from the
planned economy, and it shoulders a heavier task," said the mayor.
</P>
</TEXT>
