<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Stronger Upon Inflation Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
rose for the eighth trading day in a row, buoyed by low inflation
figures out Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The inflation data left a window of opportunity for a reduction
in interest rates by the Reserve Bank of Australia, the country's
central bank.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index closed up 32.3 points, or
1.25 percent, at 2,615.2 points after starting the day weaker in
line with offshore markets.
</P>
<P>
The surprisingly low inflation rate for the third quarter has
ensured the near term possibility of a cut in official interest
rates was the hot topic in Australian financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index rose 0.2 percent for the September
quarter for a rise of 1.3 percent in the year, the Australian
Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index surged 64.3 points, or 1.43 percent,
to 4,561.3 while the all resources index firmed 5.1 points, or
0.49 percent, to 1,052.0.
</P>
<P>
Interest rate sensitive stocks performed well amid the rate cut
speculation with the banking index gaining 72.3 points, or 1.31
percent, to 5,577.8 points.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was 40 cents higher at 21.10 Australian
dollars, ANZ bank gained 8.5 cents to 9.025 Australian dollars,
Westpac bank gained 11 cents to 9.65 Australian dollars, and the
Commonwealth Bank of Australia gained 9.1 cents to 19.53
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, diversified miner BHP shares slipped
8.7 cents to 13.251 Australian dollars, rival resource company Rio
Tinto added two cents to 20.17 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index rose 26.2 points to 1,172.0.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold bullion in Sydney closed at 292.95 U.S.
dollars an ounce up slightly from Tuesday's close at 292.70 U.S.
dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 393.53 million shares traded at a value
of 752.74 million Australian dollars, with 691 rises, 446 falls
and 397 steady.  
</P>
</TEXT>
