<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Repeals UNITA Leader's Special Legal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The National Assembly of the
Republic of Angola has repealed the law granting special legal
and ritual status for the opposition UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
The assembly adopted a resolution on the law Tuesday after it
resumed a sitting.
</P>
<P>
The law had offered a special legal status to President
Savimbi of the National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA).
</P>
<P>
According to the law, Savimbi was guaranteed the rights to
engage in the state political activities across the country and
the immunity and other rights as enjoyed by the elected state
leaders.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said that the law had been repealed because
Savimbi's behavior "has done harm to the state security, the
integrity of the national territory and the principle and values
of democracy."
</P>
<P>
"The UNITA leader has taken a stance going against the spirit
and content of the (1994) Lusaka Peace Accord, continuously causing
numerous casualties and material losses," it added.
</P>
<P>
Majority leader of the ruling People's Movement for the
Liberation of Angola (MPLA) in the national congress, Joao
Luorenco, pointed out that the repeal does not "violate the
Lusaka Peace Accord because we did not announce UNITA as
illegal."
</P>
<P>
Luorenco stressed that the Angolan government led by President
Jose Eduardo dos Santos will continue working with the UNITA
Renovation Committee which is committed to peace to implement all
stipulated in the peace protocol.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government regarded the committee as the sole
dialogist in the Angolan peace process. The breakaway group was
established in early September by the dissident UNITA members
against Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
The resolution on repealing Savimbi's special status was
passed with 115 votes for, non against and 61 abstentions. Seven
UNITA members voted for the repeal. Most of the UNITA MPs and
MPs from the Angolan National Liberation Front (ANLF) had
abstained. After the vote counting, ANLF said in a statement
that the party had abstained to show "the spirit of unity and
consensus."
</P>
<P>
After the national congress of the UNITA Renovation Committee,
17 of the 70 UNITA MPs, who had been close to Savimbi, were
suspended and two were augmented.
</P>
<P>
There are 223 seats in the Angolan national assembly and the
ruling MPLA holds 129.
</P>
<P>
According to the Lusaka accord signed by the two warring sides
in 1994, the president of the UNITA enjoys a special status in
the Angolan politics. Therefore, the Angolan parliament passed a
law on April 8, 1997, establishing the status of Savimbi as the
leader of the largest opposition party in the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the UNITA leader could freely engage in political
activities nationwide and had the rights to exchange with the
Angolan president information and views on the state politics.
</P>
<P>
In ceremonious functions, Savimbi was ranked as the second
among the party leaders holding seats in the national assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Youth Find Spouses In More Open Ways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Many Chinese youth are now
utilizing television and the Internet to find their spouses.
</P>
<P>
Several cities including Zhengzhou, capital of central China's
Henan Province, Shanghai, and Beijing have TV programs on love and
invite young people to participate. These shows are becoming more
popular all the time.
</P>
<P>
This may appear strange and hard to accept for older Chinese
for whom the choice of a spouse was considered a private matter,
and most of them found their partners through matchmakers when
they were young.
</P>
<P>
Now, things have changed completely. Young people can choose
their life-long partner on their own and don't feel shy or uneasy
when expressing their views on love and marriage and their
requirements for a future spouse. They appear on TV and talk about
love in a natural manner in front of millions in the TV audience.
</P>
<P>
"To express love openly may be better and make it more likely
you'll find the person you love," said Ma Jianfeng, an
advertisement planner who once participated on such a TV program.
</P>
<P>
On the Beijing TV show "We Meet Here Tonight" the participants
bring video tapes about their daily lives as a kind of
advertisement to help them find a mate.
</P>
<P>
Young people also make use of the Internet in their search.
</P>
<P>
One survey revealed that more than 60 percent of the young
people in Shanghai think they lack the opportunity to meet people
in other fields, and over 80 percent are confused about marriage
and love. Some experts point out that these new variety of ways to
find a spouse is the solution to such problems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 08:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptians' Entrance into Jordan to be Curbed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Jordan signed an
agreement here late Tuesday to curb the entrance of Egyptians
into the kingdom at a time when the government strictly regulates
the foreign labor market.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed by Secretary General of the
Jordanian Ministry of Labor Saleh Tarawneh and Undersecretary of
the Egyptian Ministry of Labor Ahmad Khalaf, Egypt will not allow
any Egyptian worker to enter Jordan without a contract
authenticated by Jordanian and Egyptian officials.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also stipulates that any Egyptian who wishes to
visit a relative in Jordan must carry a round-trip ticket together
with at least 150 U.S. dollars in cash.
</P>
<P>
Any Egyptian traveler coming to Jordan en route another Gulf
country must have a visa for the destination country or hold valid
residency in the destination country, according to the accord.
</P>
<P>
Young professional Egyptians are not allowed to travel to
Jordan for tourism.
</P>
<P>
About 300,000 to 500,000 foreign workers now live in Jordan, of
whom some 90 percent are Egyptians. Many Egyptians entered
Jordan on excuses of visiting relatives or traveling. The majority
of them do not have valid work permits.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government ordered the illegal Egyptian
workers either to leave the kingdom or to apply for work
permits. The deadline was extended three times, but most of them
refused to cooperate and the problem has still remained unsolved.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of this month, the government imposed new
measures to regulate the foreign labor market. Foreign workers,
including Egyptians, without valid work permits were given one
month to rectify their status. Otherwise, they will be fined
heavily and deported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
