<HEADLINE> Philippine Police Arrest More Suspected Kidnappers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine police scored anew
against kidnap-for-ransom gangs with the arrest of nine more
suspected kidnappers and the rescue of six kidnapped victims in
two separate operations in Metro Manila Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Chief Superintendent Panfilo M. Lacson, head of the
Presidential Anti-Organized Crime Task Force (PAOCTF), presented
Wednesday before the media the arrested suspects in Camp Crame,
Manila.
</P>
<P>
He immediately telephoned President Joseph Estrada to report on
the arrest of the nine suspected kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada congratulated Lacson and members of the task
force for a job well done, according to the official Philippine
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Their arrest brought to 19 the number of suspected members of
kidnap-for-ransom syndicates captured in the past five days.
</P>
<P>
Rescued by the task force were four kids from one family, their
housemaid and their driver.
</P>
<P>
They were kidnapped last Monday in the vicinity of Villalobos
Hospital in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Last week the task force smashed the so-called "50 Million
Gang" which was responsible for at least 15 kidnapping incidents
in Manila, including the kidnap-slaying of businessman Willyson
Lim Ong.
</P>
<P>
Ten members of the syndicates were arrested by the task force
in one of the most successful operations against kidnap-for-ransom
gangs in the country.
</P>
<P>
The gang had raked in more than 126 million pesos (3 million
U.S. dollars) in ransom payoff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
