<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Growth Rate Estimated at 6 Percent: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan
Van Khai said Wednesday that the national economy continues to
make comprehensive development with an estimated growth rate of
six percent and essentially remains stable on the macro level.
</P>
<P>
Khai made this announcement in a government report delivered to
the National Assembly which opened Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister admitted that Vietnam faced serious
consequences in 1998 due to prolonged natural calamities
nationwide and the regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said, in spite of serious losses caused by natural
calamities, agricultural production increased by about two
percent. food production reached 31.3 million tons, bringing per
capita food average to more than 400 kg a year, fulfilling the
target set for year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production, despite being effected by the regional
crisis, still maintained a growth rate of about 11 percent.
Services, despite reduction in some sections, climbed six percent,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said despite the drop in world prices of many important
export items of Vietnam including crude oil, coal, rubber, tea,
peanuts, garments and footwear, their export value this year is
equal to last year's figure.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister added that budget deficit has been kept at
4.2 percent of GDP in 1997 and 3.6 percent this year, the level
permitted by the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister concluded that in general, in 1998 the
national economy continued to grow, people's lives were stable,
culture and social welfare continued to develop, and political
and social stability was maintained and strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Khai pointed out weaknesses and unfavorable
involvement which is obstructing or even threatening the country's
socio-economic stability and development.
</P>
<P>
These included a drop of more than 30 percent of the economic
growth rate as compared to the average growth rate of the two
previous years, the narrowing of investment for development and
production in the fields of export, foreign investment and
services for foreigners, difficulties in maintaining balance of
macro-economy, particularly balance of state budget, and
increasing unemployment, the prime minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
