<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Sacks Five Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has removed five officials from the government in
what was considered by political analysts as a fresh offensive
against corruption.
</P>
<P>
A State House statement released Tuesday said that three
officials from the Ministry of Agriculture and Co-operatives and
two local education officers have been asked to retire.
</P>
<P>
The three officials from the ministry are Commissioner of
Co-operatives Tasilo Mahuwi, Acting Commissioner of Agriculture
E. Lujuo and Director of Manpower and Administration E. J.
Makoye.
</P>
<P>
The two education officers are from Nkasi District Education
and Sumbawanga Town Council.
</P>
<P>
Although the reasons for their retirement were not given,
political analysts said the president's measures are linked to
his war against corruption.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Rukwa Region in the southwest has offered the
president a list of corrupt officials from local judiciary,
police, education, immigration and health departments after a
secret ballot by residents there.
</P>
<P>
"This makes Rukwa to be the first region in the country to
effect the President's directive that list of public officials
from the regional and district level involved in corrupt
practices should be handed to him," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The corrupt officials have already been punished and residents
in Rukwa have renewed confidence in the government, it added.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa has retired a lot of officials in connection
with corruption scandals since he came to office in 1995.
</P>
<P>
His efforts in combating corruption has won praise from the
Attorney General Andrew Chenge, who said some big shots have got
worried after they were urged to declare personal wealth.
</P>
</TEXT>
