<HEADLINE> Vietnam Targets 5 to 6 Percent Growth Rate Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan
Van Khai Wednesday suggested a 5 to 6 percent economic growth
rate for 1999.
</P>
<P>
He made the suggestion in a government report to the National
Assembly which opened here Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Main targets include: agriculture production value to grow 3.5
to 4 percent, industrial production value to increase 10 to 11
percent, service value up 4.5 to 5.5 percent, total import-export
turnover to increase about seven percent, while the commodity
price index increase is kept below 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed that Vietnam "will continue to
embrace the on-going national renovation process and accelerate
national industrialization and modernization in the next two
years".
</P>
<P>
Presenting major policies and orientations for the country to
face the future, Khai said that in order to develop agriculture
and rural economy, increasing investment should be given to the
agriculture, forestry and fishery sectors. Land-related policies
should facilitate and increase the efficient use of arable land.
</P>
<P>
Investment should be given to boost the development of the
industrial production sector and efficient services with special
attention given to medium and small enterprises, said the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
On development investment, he said, further efforts must be
made to check the slowdown in investment flow to the economy while
effectively mobilizing available domestic resources.
</P>
<P>
Khai said a basic and long-term orientation to improve the
efficiency of the country's financial-monetary system is to fight
wastefulness, effectively implement the ordinance and decree on
thrift practice, focusing on the state-run sector.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed to the need to continue restructuring the
organization and operation of the country's banking system.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister urged that special attention should be paid
to enhancing the quality and effectiveness of the management,
organization and executive work, and the discipline and order in
all branches of activities and at all levels.
</P>
<P>
He said administrative reforms should be combined with creating
real changes in discipline and order in the party and in the
entire state system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
