<HEADLINE> Russian Foreign Minister Tables Policy Priorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov on Wednesday listed the creation of favorable external
environment for resolution of the country's domestic problems and
the defense of Russia's international status as the priorities in
its foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Moscow-based daily Izvestia, Ivanov
said Russia needed to concentrate on domestic problems and did not
want to fuel international conflicts or strive for local interests
out of those conflicts.
</P>
<P>
However, Ivanov added, Moscow would not allow it to be excluded
from settling problems involving Russian strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
"The Balkans have always been a zone of special strategic
interests for Russia," Ivanov said. "It is stability and a
peaceful solution to the problem that meet our interests."
</P>
<P>
He said the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) had no
right to use force in Kosovo without U.N. consent.
</P>
<P>
"Russia does not like attempts to put arbitrary interpretations
on provisions in the U.N. Charter for any political ends," the
foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov also reiterated Moscow's objection to the inclusion of
Ukraine and the three Baltic republics in an enlarged NATO,
stressing that he saw no reforms within NATO to make Russia
consider joining the alliance. 
</P>
