<HEADLINE> 4 Palestinians Convicted of Raiding Fatah Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Four Palestinians in the
military intelligence have been convicted by a Palestinian court
of raiding the Fatah's headquarters, which sparked clashes in
Palestinian areas claiming one life.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported Wednesday that one person was sentenced
to four years in jail and the others were given three years each
by a military court in the West Bank town of Jericho.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters of the Fatah, the movement led by Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat, were raided
early Sunday. Reports said the military intelligence forces were
searching for illegal weapons.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Fatah supporters demonstrated in the West Bank city
of Ramallah Sunday to protest the raid and clashed with
Palestinian security forces, who opened fire and killed an
18-year-old protester.
</P>
<P>
The shooting has triggered three days of demonstrations in many
Palestinian-controlled areas in the West Bank and a general
strike in Ramallah. Arafat has ordered an investigation.
</P>
<P>
Top officials in the Palestinian military intelligence have
denied that their forces were responsible for the killing, radio
reports said. Senior Palestinian prosecutors said they were
conducting an investigation into who fired the shots and
expected to bring the case into trial within the next two days.
</P>
<P>
Under the land-for-peace deal Arafat signed with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at the White House last week, the PNA
will take concrete measures to fight terrorism, including the
confiscation of illegal weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
