<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Santer Visit Will Promote China-EU Relations (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The upcoming visit by Jacques
Santer, president of the European Commission, is expected to
inject new vitality into the growth momentum in China-EU relation.
</P>
<P>
Santer, set to visit China between October 29 and November 3 at
the invitation of the Chinese Government, will lead a delegation
which will include Leon Brittan, vice-president of the European
Commission (EC) and executives from major European companies.
</P>
<P>
Local observers noted that the first visit by an EU president
in 12 years will undoubtedly be of great significance and promote
friendly China-EU relations and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Extensive efforts on the part of both sides have yielded major
progress in China-EU relations over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The highly successful China-EU Summit, the first of its kind
was in London in April, ended with a joint statement calling for
setting up a long-term stable and constructive China-EU
partnership geared to the 21st century. The move represented the
common aspiration of the people in China and the 15 nations in the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, relations have remained stable in spite of
a few minor hitches since China and the EC forged diplomatic ties
some 23 years ago. Frequent high-level exchanges and increasing
political dialog on different levels have significantly improved
and strengthened bilateral relations in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have also expanded exchanges and cooperation in
the economic and trade arena, as well as science and technology,
culture and education.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Chinese Customs show that the bilateral
trade volume for 1997 topped 43 billion US dollars, up 8.35
percent on the previous year and some 17 times the level when the
two sides established diplomatic relations in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade volume between January and September this
year stood at 33.89 billion US dollars, up 16.6 percent on the
same 1997 period. The EU is currently China's fourth largest trade
partner.
</P>
<P>
China had imported 6,864 technological items from the EU by the
end of last year, with the contract value for related items
standing at 38 billion US dollars. Related items accounted for
44.9 percent of China's total technology imports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Santer Visit Will Promote China-EU Relations (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The EU and financial institutions in its member nations have
granted China loans of approximately 12.8 billions US dollars, or
41.9 percent of total government loans.
</P>
<P>
The EU has adopted a set of positive measures this year to
improve and strengthen its ties with China. For example, the
Council of EU Foreign Ministers met in February and decided that
the the EU president and member nations will refrain from
cosponsoring human rights resolutions against China.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to China last February, Brittan said the
European Union will "pursue sensitive and highly important (human
rights) issues through dialog" and is fully prepared to avoid
unnecessary confrontations.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, the EU decided to adjust its anti-dumping
policy against China and removed the nation from the list of
nonmarket economy nations.
</P>
<P>
The June ministers council endorsed the new document calling
for the establishment of a full-fledged partnership with
China. The move was designed to improve China-EU relations and
promote political dialog, economic and trade cooperation and
increase investment, as well as to accelerate China's entry into
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
On October 5, the EU announced a decision not to levy
anti-dumping duties on unbleached cotton imported from five
countries, including China.
</P>
<P>
China welcomed and appreciated the EU decisions and continues
to follow a foreign policy based on developing stable and mutually
beneficial cooperative relations with the EU and member nations.
</P>
<P>
Strengthening the cooperation between China and the EU, two
major forces in the increasingly multipolarized world and
globalized economy, will not only be in the fundamental interest
of both parties, but will also promote cooperation between Asia
and Europe, and contribute to the peace, stability and prosperity
of the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
People have every reason to believe that President Santer's
visit will turn a new page in the growth of China-EU relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
