<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Jointly Organize International Symposium on IPR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Intellectual property rights
will become the most important and essential production factor
and will play a more decisive role in the development of the world
economy, China's top IPR official said today.
</P>
<P>
"The practice of many countries has repeatedly proved, and will
continue to prove, that the patent system and the intellectual
property system in general are a most important mechanism," said
Jiang Ying, Commissioner of the State Intellectual Property Office
(SIPO).
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks at the opening of an international IPR
symposium on "The Protection of Intellectual Property for the 21st
Century" jointly organized by the China Intellectual Property
Society (CIPS) and the American Intellectual Property Law
Association (AIPLA).
</P>
<P>
"The mechanism not only promotes the creation, spread and use
of knowledge, but also effectively protects the newest
intellectual achievements of mankind," she said.
</P>
<P>
"For the purpose of keeping pace with the trend of IPR
protection in the 21st century, and in order to conform to the
development of the intellectual-property economy, we must keep
learning and monitoring the newest trend of international IPR
protection, and earnestly researching new issues arising in new
technical fields," she said.
</P>
<P>
Michael Kirk, AIPLA's executive director, said the patent
system has been developing for more than 200 years in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Although China adopted such a system only two decades ago, it
has established a set of fairly good laws and regulations, said
Kirk, a former U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary of Commerce and
former Deputy Commissioner of Patents and Trademarks.
</P>
<P>
All countries throughout the world should learn from each other
and reach mutual understanding and confidence for the common goal,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the last ten years, China has formulated and put into
effect trademark laws, patent and copyright laws and fair
competition laws. In addition, a set of intellectual property
regulations has also been enacted including Regulations on the
Protection of Computer Software and Regulations on New Plant
Varieties.
</P>
<P>
China joined the World Intellectual Property Organization
(WIPO) in 1980 and subsequently acceded to international
conventions on IPR protection.
</P>
<P>
Some 180 delegates from around the world are attending the
three-day symposium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
