<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Companies Expect Better Revenue Growth in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Companies in Malaysia are
expected to have better performance with their gross revenue
increasing by 3.8 percent in the second half of 1998, according to
a business expectations survey.
</P>
<P>
Some 270 limited companies covered in the survey estimated a
total gross revenue of 125.8737 billion ringgit (33.124 billion
U.S. dollars) for the second half of 1998, representing an
increase of 3.8 percent from the 121.2087 billion ringgit (31.897
billion U.S. dollars) achieved in the first half, the Department
of Statistics said in its monthly report released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said 120 companies, accounting for 51 percent of the total
gross revenue in the first half of 1998, expect to operate at a
higher level in the second half, 103 companies, accounting for
29.8 percent of the revenue in first half, will operate below the
past level while the remaining 47 companies will continue to
operate at the same level as before.
</P>
<P>
Of the 13 sectors covered, 10 sectors are optimistic of better
days ahead, projecting increases in their gross revenue, while the
remaining three see a leaner second half.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the sectors projecting revenue
increases included the oil palm sector; insurance, real estate and
business services; retail; petroleum mining and electricity;
wholesale; manufacturing; hotels; rubber; construction as well as
transport.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the three sectors expected to report a drop in
gross revenue were logging; telecommunications as well as banks
and other financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The 270 companies are expected to employ 433,851 workers in the
second half, slightly lower than 434,062 workers in the first half
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
