<HEADLINE> China Works to Increase Building Materials Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- China is working diligently to
set up foreign markets for ceramics and plate glass in order to
reverse the decline in building materials exports sparked by the
financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
A official with the State Administration of Building Materials
said that related exports, mainly cement, to southeast Asian
nations have dropped sharply during 1998. He called on departments
and enterprises to explore world markets and focus quality control.
</P>
<P>
The official stressed that building materials firms should
extend great effort to protect their market share in southeast
Asia, and should at the same time develop new markets in the
Middle East and Africa.
</P>
<P>
China's ceramics industry, which has a longstanding history,
has experienced rapid growth and currently produces some 10
billion units annually, or about 60 percent of the world's total
production for related products.
</P>
<P>
Chinese ceramics are exported to some 150 countries and
regions, with annual earning from exports hitting 1.9 billion
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, major producers should accelerate technological
renovations to reduce pollution, cut energy consumption and both
processing and quality in order to increase the export potential
for ceramics, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
