<HEADLINE> Improved China Upbeat about Volleyball Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 12-member Chinese team left here Wednesday for the 13th
Women's Volleyball World Championship, which starts in Kagoshima,
Japan, on November 3.
</P>
<P>
Head coach Lang Ping, a pivot player in the all-mighty Chinese
team which won the 1986 championship in Czechoslovakia, said
their goal is to make the top three.
</P>
<P>
"To win the title is beyond our strength," Lang said. "But
we'll do our best for better placing."
</P>
<P>
Bracketed with Croatia, runners-up in the European
Championships, old rivals South Korea and Thailand in the
preliminary round, China don't expect real obstacle to qualify
for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
Finishing a disappointing eighth place in last championships,
China would feel headache if they meet Cuba, winners four years
ago in Brazil who are drawn with Italy, the United States and
Bulgaria, on the way to the last four.
</P>
<P>
The first three finishers in each of the four
preliminary-round groups will go for the playoffs, wherein they
will be re-drawn in two groups. Top two of each playoffs group
will vie for the title.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese roster (players number in parenthesis):
</P>
<P>
Lai Yawen (1), Li Yan (2), Cui Yongmei (3), Zhu Yunying (4),
Wu Yongmei (5), He Qi (7), Yin Yin (8), Li Yizhi (9), Wang Ziling
(10), Sun Yue (11), Qiu Aihua (12), Wang Lina (15). 
