<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Has Potentials to Emerge as Major Ceramic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has the potentials to
become one of the major ceramic exporting countries, provided
integrated institutional and individual efforts are made to
rejuvenate the sector.
</P>
<P>
This view was expressed by speakers at a day-long seminar on
"Design and Attractive Packaging of Ceramic Goods for Japanese
Market" jointly organized by the Japan External Trade Organization
(JETRO) and The Export Promotion Bureau (EPB) of Bangladesh here
Tuesday, The Daily Star newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has a vast potential market, but most of its ceramic
industries are still far from the international standard in
producing quality goods, speakers pointed out, suggesting adoption
of sophisticated techniques like quality control, timely shipment,
excellent design and attractive packaging.
</P>
<P>
"Availability of the main basic ingredients for ceramic
products like moist clay and cheap labor force add to the
competitive advantages of the country over other countries," they
observed.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the biggest donor for Bangladesh, can be one of the
latter's largest importers by raising the quality of ceramic
products through transferring technology as well as knowledge to
Bangladeshi entrepreneurs, EPB Vice Chairman Anwarul Bar Chowdhury
said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that Japan would help arrange a single country fair in
Tokyo in March next year to promote Bangladeshi products to the
Japanese people.
</P>
<P>
JETRO's representative in Bangladesh Yichi Bamba said that his
organization has taken a long-term program for the development of
the sector since Bangladesh's ceramic products have a bright
prospect for the Japanese market.
</P>
<P>
He assured that his organization which runs under the Japanese
Ministry of International Trade and Industry would continue its
endeavors for the development of various sectors in Bangladesh,
especially garments and ceramics to increase export from
Bangladesh to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh earned over 492.5 million taka (10.2 million U.S.
dollars) during the last fiscal year (July 1997-June 1998) by
exporting ceramic goods to about 30 European countries and the
United States of America. At present, six ceramic industries are
exporting their products according to the official statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
