<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Nuclear Submarine Project Yet to Take Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Despite investments of 20
billion rupees (500 million U.S. dollars) over the past 15 years,
India's nuclear submarine program is yet to take off, a national
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The design of the submarine, called as advanced technology
vehicle, has not been frozen and the submarine's keel has not been
laid, according to the Hindustan Times.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted highly-placed sources as saying that the Naval
Headquarters, concerned at the slow pace of the vehicle, has
proposed a "technical audit" of the project to assess whether the
progress thus far justified the phenomenal expenditure on it.
</P>
<P>
Most of the money for the project is believed to have been
spent on obtaining design drawings from abroad, civilian
construction work, establishing test beds, procuring related
equipment and overseas visits of key personnel.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that a substantial amount of the money has been
spent on translation of design from Russian to English and a large
number of trips made by Defense Ministry and service officials to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
The design and development of the nuclear submarine, a joint
project of the Department of Atomic Energy, Defense Research and
Development Organization and the Indian Navy, was started some 15
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Defense analysts here said the availability of a nuclear
submarine has a significant bearing on India's decision to acquire
a minimum nuclear deterrent.
</P>
<P>
The project, which received focused attention in the early
1980s by the late prime minister Indira Gandhi, revolved around
the construction of a titanium hull and a nuclear reactor to
propel it.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition of the Chakre, a Soviet origin Charlie-I class
nuclear submarine, by India on a three-year lease in January 1988,
is understood to have provided useful inputs both to the project
design and training of personnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
