<HEADLINE> China Develops Bohai Sea Oil Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Shengli Oil Field, China's
second largest oil reserve, has recorded a major breakthrough in
oil exploration with development of the Chengdao deposit in the
Bohai Sea off the nation's east coast.
</P>
<P>
The new oil field has an annual output capacity of 1.05 million
tons and is the largest offshore oil deposit in the Bohai Bay.
</P>
<P>
An official from the China National Petrochemical Corp
(Sinopec) said the geological structure in the area complicated
the exploration process. Shengli used a vast array of advanced
onshore oil development to tap the Chengdao field, including 3-D
seismic surveys and oil reserve tracking technology.
</P>
<P>
The oil field said that it can produce 2.12 million tons of oil
and 367 million cubic meters of gas a year in the Bohai area.
</P>
<P>
Industry officials expect even greater progress in oil and gas
exploration in the Bohai area, with reserves to be proven
estimated at 60 million tons of and over 10 billion cubic meters
of gas this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
