<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Terracotta Warriors in Red, Green 2,000 Years Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Most of the terracotta warriors
and horses inspected by U.S. President Bill Clinton in Shaanxi
Province when he was visiting China months ago were grey, the
color of clay. But archaeologists say they were mainly red and
green more than 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The terracotta figurines of the Qin Dynasty (221-207 BC) were
decorated in red, green, blue, yellow, purple and brown, Liu
Zhancheng, an archaeologist at the Museum of Terracotta Warriors
and Horses in Shaanxi Province, northwest China, said today.
</P>
<P>
"The clothes of the terracotta warriors were mainly red and
green, but the colors have peeled off," he said.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists studied the little color remaining on the
figurines when they were unearthed, and 43 percent of the clay
warriors were in green robes, 32 percent were in red robes; about
52 percent were wearing green trousers and 18 percent red trousers.
</P>
<P>
Liu explained that red, the color of blood and fire, represents
strength, status and firmness, while green symbolizes vigor and
fertility.
</P>
<P>
"The artists of the Qin Dynasty gave life to the clay warriors
with color," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
The terracotta warriors and horses were discovered in Lintong
County of Shaanxi Province in 1974. Since then, more than 100
chariots, 600 clay horses, 8,000 clay warriors and a large number
of ancient weapons have been unearthed in three huge pits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
