<HEADLINE> Commerce Brisk in North China's Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Commerce has become brisk in
Tianjin, the largest port city in north China, as the city has
made painstaking efforts to expand this sector.
</P>
<P>
The city is now dotted with a galaxy of grandiose shopping
centers, shopping malls, chain stores and many kinds of
wholesale markets.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months this year, Tianjin chalked up 42.77
billion yuan in retail sales of consumer commodities, up nine
percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the volume was accomplished by commercial
enterprises with non-public ownerships, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
The city now has 1,129 chain stores of various kinds, which did
2.16 billion yuan in retail sales from January to September,
exceeding the retail sales volume of 1.3 billion yuan for all of
1997.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin also has an assortment of 701 markets, including three
built with outside investments totaling 30 million yuan. In the
first nine months, major wholesale markets in the city did 29
billion yuan worth of spot trade, up 12.1 percent over the same
period last year.  
</P>
