<HEADLINE> Wellington on Arson Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A house to house campaign
was launched Wednesday to advise householders in Wellington,
Capital of New Zealand, how to avoid being the target of an
arsonist and minimize danger to property.
</P>
<P>
Over the past week, a spate of suspicious fires were found in
central Wellington. Although the fires, which were deliberately
lit outside occupied houses and churches, caused minor damage, the
local police fear a serial arsonist, or arsonists, is targeting
inner city buildings.
</P>
<P>
Detective Senior Sergeant Ron Chatt of Wellington was quoted as
 saying Wednesday that up to now no firm suspects have been
identified as connected to the fire.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking at past arsonists," he said. The fires were
definitely suspicious and deliberately lit, and though one person
could be responsible, he was not ruling out the possibility there
was more than one person.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, most of the latest suspicious
fires were lit between midnight and 2 a.m., when occupants were
sleeping inside.
</P>
<P>
Through the media, local police and fire service urged
households to fit smoke alarms, plan escape routes, lock garages,
basements and sheds and leave no rubbish laying outside. Kits
would be also delivered in the areas of potential risk.
</P>
<P>
According to the New Zealand Press Association (NZPA), in
Auckland, the biggest city in New Zealand, police are also
looking for arsonists who started fires at three buildings in the
Auckland suburb of Pt Chevalier within two hours of each other
early Monday.
</P>
<P>
The NZPA quoted local investigators as saying that the fires
were deliberately lit and there were at least two arsonists.
</P>
</TEXT>
