<HEADLINE> Myanmar Enhances Medicine Practitioners' Skills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has been paying
attention to enhancing the skills of the traditional medicine
practitioners by conducting successive training programs in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Traditional medicine development projects including opening of
more related hospitals and treatment centers and researches on
traditional medicines for manufacturing standard ones are being
carried out under the National Health Plan, Wednesday's The New
Light of Myanmar quoted Myanmar leader Lieutenant General Khin
Nyunt as saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of a training course of traditional
medicine practitioners here Tuesday, Khin Nyunt, first secretary
of the Myanmar State Peace and Development Council, disclosed that
more traditional hospitals have already been opened in Pathein,
Myeik and Taunggyi in addition to those in the capital of Yangon
and Mandalay.
</P>
<P>
A total of 128 traditional medicine practitioners from
different parts of the country are attending the 10-month course.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, there were three indigenous
hospitals and 194 dispensaries with more than 400 practitioners in
Myanmar in 1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar enacted the Traditional Medicine Law in July 1996 to
uplift the potency of indigenous medicine and to ensure safety for
users, issuing patents and licenses to entrepreneurs and testing
traditional medicines in advanced laboratories.
</P>
<P>
So far, 700 local entrepreneurs have been permitted to produce
and sell their medicinal products.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has been using traditional medicines since ancient
times which are still popular among people in both urban and rural
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
