<HEADLINE> Russia to Improve Relations With EU: Primakov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said here Tuesday that Russia will close the
distance with the European Union (EU) by moving ahead with the
economic reform.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima and EU
Commission President Jacques Santer, Primakov told a press
conference that Russia will repay its foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said that Russia is trying to establish a market
economy and, "We don't want a monetarism which is not supported by
the people."
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that the European Reconstruction and Development
Bank would provide Russia with assistance.
</P>
<P>
Primakov was in Austria for the Russian-EU summit on behalf of
ailing Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who cancelled his plan on
Monday to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Klima, whose country holds the current rotating EU presidency,
hopes that Russia will speed up its economic reform and pay
foreign loans, saying an immediate implementation of the reform
program is a prerequisite for re-building investor confidence in
the economy.
</P>
<P>
According to Klima, the Russian-EU Coordination Commission will
meet in Moscow in December to discuss bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Primakov, Austrian President Thomas
Klestil said that as a partner, Russia plays a pivotal role in
maintaining the stability and security in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, an accord on cultural cooperation was signed
here by Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel and his
Russian counterpart, Igor Ivanov, to replace the one signed in
1968 between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Primakov returned to Russia after ending his one-day trip
here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
