<HEADLINE> U.S. Girl Gymnast Settles with Parents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After she ran away from home for one week and sued her
parents, Moceanu's parents agreed to let her to be a legal adult
to handle her own financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
David Gray, an attorney with the law office representing
Moceanu, said her parents have dropped their resistance to having
her declared a legal adult and that an agreement would be
presented Wednesday to a family court judge.
</P>
<P>
"Her legal disabilities as a minor will be removed," Gray said.
</P>
<P>
Moceanu and her parents made a statement, saying: "The parties
have met amongst themselves and as a family unit have resolved
their differences. It is anticipate that an agreement will be
submitted to Judge John Montgomery for approval."
</P>
<P>
The announcement achieved after the both sides met Tuesday in
their first meetings since she left home and filed a lawsuit
demanding to be declared a legal adult so she could get answers
about how her earnings are being spent.
</P>
<P>
Moceanu believed her father, Dumitru Moceanu, had squandered
much of the money to build a gymnasium in the Houston suburb.
</P>
<P>
According to Yarrell, the trust is structured so that Moceanu
won't gain control over the assets until she turns 35. But if the
Moceanus' parental rights are severed, she might be able to gain
access to the funds early, Yarell said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
