<HEADLINE> Polluted Water Kills Five Million Kids Each Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Experts said on Tuesday
more than one billion people worldwide have suffered from stomach
infections, while five million children die each year due to
non-potable water.
</P>
<P>
On the second day of a meeting on rainwater collection in
Mexico, Manuel Anaya said that 30,000 people died of diarrhea
every day.
</P>
<P>
Anaya said the total fresh water reserves all over the earth
amounted to 35 million cubic kilometers, accounting only for three
percent of the total 1.3 billion cubic kilometers of water.
</P>
<P>
However, the fresh water demand worldwide will reach 7,000
cubic kilometers in 2000 so that a new technology will have to be
used to meet the requirement, Anaya said.
</P>
<P>
At least 100 countries are suffering from droughts and over one
billion people have insufficient access to water and food, he said.
</P>
<P>
Spanish researchers Jose Luis Rubio and Luis Racatal said that
900 million people are hit by the impact of scarce rainfall and
over 360 million hectares of desertified land still exist in 81
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
