<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiat's Chief Expects Lower Profits for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Warnings from Italy's biggest
car-maker Fiat that its end-of-year profits could be lower than
the previous year were confirmed Tuesday by the company honorary
chairman Gianni Agnelli.
</P>
<P>
"Fiat's second half will be worse than the first half,"
Agnelli told reporters. The Fiat group's accounts were "good but
not excellent" and a board meeting would be held at the end
of 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
In September, Fiat reported first-half sales up 8 percent but
warned that profits were expected to drop for the whole year of
1998, partly due to a fall-off in sales in crisis-stricken Brazil,
where Fiat sells 20 percent of its cars.
</P>
<P>
After four years of steady annual growth of four to five
percent, the Brazilian auto market is now in dire straits, with
sales down 45 percent so far this year over the same period of
1997.
</P>
<P>
This week, Fiat was forced to suspend production in its
Brazilian factories in order to limit the inventory of unsellable
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
In Italy, the end of government sales-promoting incentives in
July has also knocked a significant dent in Fiat profits.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of 1998, Fiat's pre-tax profits plunged
11.6 percent, from 2.26 trillion Italy lire (some 1.378 billion
U. S. dollars) to 2 trillion lire (about 1.2 billion dollars),
which was coupled with a fall in the operating profits.
</P>
<P>
Another sign of problems ahead was the fact that productivity
in industrial activities dipped from 4.4 percent in the first half
of 1997 to 3.3 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Revenues for the year are now expected to reach 90-92 trillion
lire (54.9-56.1 billion dollars) instead of 94 trillion lire (57.3
billion dollars) and profits are expected to fall below the 2.46
trillion lire (1.5 billion dollars) recorded last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the managing director of Deutsche Bank Fondi, Mario
Noera, said Tuesday that, sooner or later, Fiat would have to give
in to the growing trend towards consolidation in the automobile
industry.
</P>
<P>
The mega-merger between Germany's Daimler Benz and the American
giant Chrysler had paved the way and the survival of car companies
in the future would depend on their ability to form global
alliances.
</P>
<P>
Fiat's new chairman, Paolo Fresco, stuck to the company line of
no international alliances when unveiling the firm's 1998-2002
industrial plan last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
