<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls for Cooperation Between State, Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Lieutenant
General Tin Oo has called for endeavors and cooperation between
the state and private sectors to bring about long-term and firm
economic development in the country.
</P>
<P>
At a coordination meeting with private entrepreneurs here
Tuesday, Tin Oo, second secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and
Development Council, said only when there is increase in
production, especially agricultural production, will the social
sector and politics of the state develop proportionately.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if the nation is to rely on external assistance
and copy ways and means of developed nations including those of
the West Bloc, the nation will lose its own national stand and
fall into a state of vassal which has no political and economic
freedom.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that although Myanmar was once famous as a
granary of the Southeast Asia region, there were economic
uncertainties about paddy cultivation as priority was given to
local consumption, bringing about a marked decrease in the export
of rice.
</P>
<P>
He cited the average tonnage of annual rice export which was
just at six figures then.
</P>
<P>
After the market-oriented economic system was introduced in
late 1988, he said, the cultivation and production of paddy
increased and over 16 million tons of paddy can be produced
annually, while controlling the export of rice for the sake of
local consumption.
</P>
<P>
Continued efforts are being made to meet the target of
producing 20 million tons of paddy annually with 2 tons per acre
(4.93 tons per hectare) yield, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's paddy production in
the 1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March, was registered at
17.3 million tons, of which only 28,300 tons of rice were
exported. The rice export figures for the first six months of this
year were 17,600 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
