<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland to Relax Restrictions on Economic Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Poland will cut the number of
industrial activities requiring licenses from 28 to six in an
attempt to relax economic restrictions and reduce the country's
intervention in the business field.
</P>
<P>
The statement has been included in the draft law on Economic
Activities, which was endorsed by the Polish government on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The six areas in which licenses are still required include
mining and prospecting, the manufacturing and marketing of
explosives, arms, ammunition and liquid fuels, bodyguard services,
airline transportation, and the construction of toll roads.
</P>
<P>
The government suggested canceling licenses for such activities
as starting a new business or inland fishing.
</P>
<P>
Another 14 former licensed areas, which include the
manufacturing and marketing of cigarettes and liquors as well as
international transportation, will be subject to general approval,
according to the new law.
</P>
<P>
The Law on Economic Activities, which governs economic
activities in Poland, grants equal rights to both domestic and
foreign entities in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
