<HEADLINE> Shanghai Starts Major River Purification Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
industrial city, will spend 8.65 billion yuan (1.04 billion US
dollars) on the first phase of a major program to clean the Suzhou
River.
</P>
<P>
The first of 10 projects in the initial phase will include the
construction of sewage disposal plants, and various water
conservation and environmental protection projects.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai plans to carry out a total of 17 projects to eliminate
river pollution within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The new plants will treat wastewater which was previously
discharged directly into the river.
</P>
<P>
The city will also build additional pump stations to increase
the river's water volume to improve the natural filtration process
and will introduce oxygenation to improve water quality.
</P>
<P>
The pollution reduction program will include removing more
wharves from the central city area. Some 60-odd wharves have
already been dismantled or removed along a five km stretch of the
river.  
</P>
</TEXT>
