<HEADLINE> Bangkok Bank in Phnom Penh to Close US Dollar Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Bangkok Bank is
downsizing its Phnom Penh Branch by closing all of its U.S. dollar
accounts by the end of this month, it was learned here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision to close the U.S. dollar accounts, which total
more than 1,000, was made in September due to economic crisis in
the region and the political risk in Cambodia, according to branch
manager Thewakun Chanakun.
</P>
<P>
The Thai-owned Bangkok Bank branch, established in June 1992,
also plans to cut its staff by 40 percent, laying off 10 local
employees and sending back to Thailand three expatriate staff
members.
</P>
<P>
The manager said the bank has a very high cost to manage the
U.S. dollar cash in Cambodia since the bank has to pay interest
rate, take risk from unstable currency exchange and rampage of
fake banknotes in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
"It is very difficult to manage cash during hard times,
politically and economically," he added.
</P>
<P>
Thewakun disclosed that branches in Jakarta and Vientiane are
similarly being downsized.
</P>
<P>
Several foreign and domestic banks have fallen on hard times.
The Thai-owned Siam City Bank shut its doors on October 1 and the
Cambodia Farmers Bank is closing. According to National Bank of
Cambodia officials, Indonesia's LippoBank is downsizing its
branch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
