<HEADLINE> Brazilian President Justifies Austerity Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso appeared on TV Tuesday night to justify an
austerity program approved by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
In his first TV appearance since his re-election on October 4,
Cardoso said that the spending cuts and tax increase were
necessary to slash the country's 65 billion U.S. dollar deficit.
</P>
<P>
He said the 1999 budget would be reduced by 7.9 billion
dollars, pledging the cut would not affect farmers, exporters and
the capital goods sector.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso said that he would also ask the congress to reduce the
federal government's anti-poverty programs which he described as
"unjust".
</P>
<P>
The programs at a staggering cost of 16 billion dollars a year
benefited only about 900,000 people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso also announced tax hikes and interest rates cut of
between 19 and 49.5 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, Cardoso's economic team and the IMF have tried
to work out ways to slash the deficit.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is a victim of the financial crisis that began last year
in Asia and later shifted to Russia before moving here. In the
past two months, investors have withdrawn about 25 billion dollars
from the country. 
</P>
