<HEADLINE> No Food Supply Problem in Myanmar: Says Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Lieutenant
General Khin Nyunt said Tuesday that there will be no food supply
problem in the country as plans are being laid down on the
national scale to ensure significant growth in agricultural
production.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with members of local authorities at the Central
Command Headquarters in Mandalay, Khin Nyunt, first secretary of
the Myanmar State Peace and Development Council, said such efforts
are also being made to provide humanitarian assistance to some
Southeast Asian nations which are facing food problems.
</P>
<P>
Most of the states and divisions in Myanmar can now produce
sufficient rice as the government has transformed vacant and
virgin lands into cultivated areas and extended farming with added
momentum, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, in the 1997-98 fiscal year
which ended in March, fallow land in Myanmar came to 1.1 million
hectares and cultivable wasteland 7.89 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
The country expanded cultivated land with sown area under crops
reaching 12.51 million hectares in the year, 189,540 hectares more
than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's paddy production in the 1997-98 was registered at
17.3 million tons, of which 28,300 tons of rice were exported. The
rice export figures for the first six months of this year were
17,600 tons.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's agriculture, accounting for 36 percent of the gross
domestic product and 35 percent of the export in value, grew by
2.9 percent in output value in the fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
