<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crime Jump Spurs New Police Plan in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Beijing vehicle owners can rest
a bit easier, say police who are stepping up efforts against
property crimes, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The city's branch of the Public Security Bureau is increasing
its centralized co-ordination and keeping its eyes when the sun
goes down, a senior police official said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"We will not only enforce our night patrolling and set up
all-year-long check points, but also carry on joint actions among
districts and counties, instead of separate ones," said Ruan
Zengyi, deputy-director of Beijing Public Security Bureau.
</P>
<P>
He went on to explain that because most crimes occurred at
night, check-points were efficient in holding back criminals on
the run, and separate actions of any district or county only
chased criminals from one part of the capital to another.
</P>
<P>
Ruan made this remark in a report to the Beijing Municipal
People's Political Consultative Conference as a part of the
bureau's campaign starting this year to solicit people's
supervision of their work.
</P>
<P>
The capital has seen more than 6,000 break-ins, robberies and
burglaries this year, most of which happened at intersections, on
overpasses, below underpasses, or among the residential buildings
where the city's urban area joins its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
A new trend in the city is vehicle theft.
</P>
<P>
Admitting the bureau has not filed all these cases for
investigation and prosecution, Ruan said these types of cases
increased from 2,300 in 1996 to this year's 3,700, a record high.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
