<HEADLINE> Southwest China Lake Facing Serious Environment Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Dianchi, a famous freshwater
lake in southwest China's Yunnan Province, has shrunk by 14 square
kilometers over the past ten years and is under the threat of
serious pollution, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Villagers of Long Men village in the Xishan district of the
provincial capital Kunming have reclaimed about 3.2 hectares of
land around the lake in the past several years, the paper said,
quoting an official of the Dianchi Protection Office.
</P>
<P>
On October 19, two reporters from Yunnan Television Station,
who were working on a story about illegal land reclamation, were
beaten by the villagers in Long Men.
</P>
<P>
The protection office said the city government promulgated the
Dianchi Protection Rules in 1988. But many residents around the
lake ignore the rules and have reclaimed the shores and sold them
to business people who have set up various restaurants and hotels.
</P>
<P>
Over 70 hotels, holiday resorts and other entertainment places
have been set up on the shore of the lake, dumping polluted water
and rubbish into the lake.
</P>
<P>
People from Jinning County near the lake are blowing up rocks
on the lake shore. A lot of broken stones and silt are being
dumped into the lake, disrupting its natural flow of water.
</P>
<P>
A lot of garbage was piled in Hewei village on the eastern bank
of the lake, then thrown into the lake.
</P>
<P>
Some departments governing shipping management at Dianchi
issued sailing licenses without restraint, and now over 300
motor-driven ships carry visitors around the lake. Oil in the fuel
tanks of these ships often leaks into the water, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The Yunnan provincial government and Kunming city government
have invested over 600 million U.S. dollars to tackle the problems
at Dianchi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
