<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- Just hours after taking office Tuesday, the cabinet of
Germany's new chancellor Gerhard Schroeder made its first foreign
policy decision offering to send observers to Kosovo to help
monitor Yugoslavia's withdrawal of troops from the region.
</P>
<P>
Up to 200 German observers would participate in the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) mission
in Kosovo, said government spokesman Uwe-Karl Heye after the first
meeting of the new German cabinet Tuesday evening. (Germany-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Russia has asked the United States for
significant quantities of food aid due to sharp drop in its grain
harvest and increased cost of imported food after the rouble's
devaluation, U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is in our interest as a country to do our best to
accommodate their needs," Glickman told reporters. "But there are
still some things to be worked out relating to accountability to
make sure that whatever food we provide gets to people."
(US-Russia-Food Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Republicans have out-raised Democrats by
roughly 92 million dollars, but both parties are bringing in more
money than they did for the last mid-term election in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The record-setting figures were released Tuesday by the Federal
Election Commission (FEC) even though as an independent review of
campaign finances suggested that relatively few races are
competitive this election season. (US-Campaign-Money)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Tuesday welcomed the
withdrawal of Serb troops from Kosovo but said the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) would remain vigilant to ensure
Belgrade fully complied with U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
"This is a chance, not a guarantee," Clinton said at a White
House event in which he warned Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic he must "stay in compliance" with the rules spelled out
by the international community. (US-Kosovo-Albright 1st lead)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Tuesday
that Britain would insist that two suspects in the Lockerbie
bombing must serve their sentences in Scotland if they were found
guilty.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in British parliament Tuesday, Cook said: "We have
been able to respond positively to all the issues raised by the
Libyan legal team, with the exception of their demand that if
convicted the two accused should not serve their sentence in a
Scottish prison." (UK-Lockerbie Bombers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM-- Senior Israeli politicians urged the right wingers
Tuesday to halt the wild incitement campaign against Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman said it would be "very grave" if
there would be a repetition of the incitement waged against former
prime minister Yitzhak Rabin, who was assassinated by a right-wing
extremist in 1995. (Israel-Incitement) 
</P>
</TEXT>
