<HEADLINE> Britain, France Congratulate D'Alema's Win in Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 27 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin congratulated their
Italian counterpart, Massimo D'Alema, for winning a confidence
vote in the Senate on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Recalling his meeting in London with D'Alema in September,
Blair hoped he and D'Alema could "continue working together in
close cooperation for the purpose of tackling common problems
together."
</P>
<P>
In his response, D'Alema said he hopes to seize the new
opportunity to quickly start up close cooperation between the two
governments.
</P>
<P>
"I am referring especially to bilateral relations ... as well
as the contribution we can provide together to the process of
European integration, to peace and national unity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jospin, in his message, said he was convinced Italy and France
will "pursue close cooperation developed out of a long tradition"
and affirmed that these ties "have been especially enriched in
recent years."
</P>
<P>
D'Alema, a communist-turned-social democrat, was sworn in a
week ago as the head of Italy's 56th government since World War
II. He won a confidence vote in the lower house last Friday.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema's predecessor, Romano Prodi, resigned on October 9
after losing a lower house confidence vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
