<HEADLINE> Romania Again Voices Wish to Join EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu reiterated here Tuesday his country's wish to join
the European Union (EU) and expressed his hope that Romania would
have Finland's support in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference Tuesday evening, the Romanian
president stressed that his country has greatly improved its ties
with neighboring countries in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that Ukraine and Russia do not oppose
Romania's bid to join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) as much as they used to do demonstrated Bucharest's
improved relations with its neighboring nations.
</P>
<P>
Romania is seeking to join NATO because it wants to have a
greater guarantee of security, he said.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu arrived here earlier on Tuesday on a two-day
official visit at the invitation of Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari. This is the first ever visit to Finland by a Romanian
president in 71 years.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said that during their talks, the two
presidents exchanged views on bilateral relations, the enlargement
of the EU, which now has 15 member nations, the security of
Europe, the situation in the Balkan region, and other wide-ranging
issues.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to make further efforts to promote bilateral trade
and economic cooperation, the sources said. In 1997, trade between
the two countries reached a record high of 190 million Finnish
markkas (about 38 million U.S. dollars)
</P>
<P>
The sources said Finland has promised to support Romania's bid
to join the EU.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Finnish Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen had
talks with her Romanian counterpart Andrei Plesu on issues of
common concern.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two countries signed an agreement on avoidance
of double taxation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
