<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Urged to Continue Exporting Tea to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Commerce Minister
Kingsley T. Wickremaratne has urged the country's tea industry to
continue tea exports to Russia, according to the official Daily
News Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Russia accounts for 25 percent of Sri Lanka's tea exports but
due to the financial crisis in Russia and its inability to settle
accounts, Sri Lanka's tea exports were temporarily suspended
recently.
</P>
<P>
Wickremaratne told the paper that if Sri Lanka halted tea
exports to Russia, she will be losing that market for ever as
other tea exporting countries like Kenya, India and Indonesia are
waiting to break into the market.
</P>
<P>
He said it augurs well for Sri Lanka that Russia, which has
banned a large number of imports into that country in the wake of
its financial crisis, has not banned the import of Sri Lanka's
teas.
</P>
<P>
The minister believes that the Russian monetary crisis was a
temporary one and would blow over soon. Even the Russian
ambassador had assured him that the importers of his country would
honor their financial commitments, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Russia bought 27.6 million kilograms of tea from Sri Lanka for
the first quarter of this year. The Russian crisis commenced in
around August from which month Sri Lanka's tea exports to that
country had slowed down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
