<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts View Central America Major Route for Drug Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Experts and officials from
23 North and South American countries warned on Tuesday that
Central America has become a major route for rings smuggling tons
of cocaine to the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
As U.S. anti-drug leader Barry McCaffrey visited Mexico to
prepare a high-level anti-narcotics meeting, a report released
here by the Inter-American Drug Control Commission said Colombian
cocaine was the main product being smuggled north.
</P>
<P>
Commission members said that Central America had changed from a
mere transit zone for cocaine sold in the U.S. to a drug users'
region, due to the traffickers' practice of paying go-betweens
with drugs instead of money.
</P>
<P>
McCaffrey said Monday in Mexico City that the U.S. government
had spent three billion dollars this year to try to reduce drug
use in the world's largest market.
</P>
<P>
He said drug lords were changing their routes, abandoning cargo
flights and shipping cocaine by sea instead.
</P>
<P>
The experts, who are meeting behind closed doors here, said the
smugglers were using international waters to ship drugs to
U.S. territories in the Caribbean, especially Puerto Rico, to
evade anti-drug police.
</P>
<P>
They said smugglers are now increasingly using yachts, cargo
ships, fishing boats and even cruise ships to smuggle cocaine.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the attorney general's office in Mexico announced
Tuesday that it had seized more than 20 tons of drugs this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
