<HEADLINE> Bank Indonesia Certificate Rate Expected to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia Governor Sjahril
Sabirin Tuesday said the SBI (Bank Indonesia Certificate) rate is
expected to fall further next week, national newspapers reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The SBI rate has been falling gradually from 70 percent to 58
percent, and it is seen falling again next week," Sabirin told
reporters following a meeting with President B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed optimism that the rupiah rate against the
U.S. dollar will remain to stay at least at the current level in
the coming weeks, although the nation is nearing a crucial week
before the special session of the People's Consultative Assembly
(MPR).
</P>
<P>
The country is scheduled to hold a special session of the MPR,
the country's top policy-making body, from November 10 to 13 to
set the date for next year's general election and adopt other
measures to accelerate the democratization process.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin explained that various factors, including politics,
would continue to cause fluctuations in the exchange rate against
the U.S. dollar, but the increasing credibility of the
government's economic reform program and signs of improvement in
the economy would offset any negative factors.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has appreciated by about 40 percent since late last
month. The currency remained flat at 7,400 rupiah to the U.S.
dollar Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin said last week that the rupiah could strengthen to
between 6,000 and 6,500 rupiah by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The government had earlier targeted the currency to be at
10,000 rupiah by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin stressed that Bank Indonesia has no intention of
applying the intervention band, as the current system is working
effectively and the rupiah continues to strengthen against the
greenback.
</P>
<P>
He however added that the central bank was studying various
alternatives to the current free float system.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the central bank announced Tuesday that Indonesia's
net international reserves increased by 64.9 million U.S. dollars
to 13.9 billion U.S. dollars in the week ending October 23 from
13.8 billion U.S. dollars in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The increase resulted from foreign loan disbursements and
foreign exchange revenue from the export of oil and natural gas,
the central bank said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It added that the reserve level was above the 11.67 billion
U.S. dollars minimum level set by the International Monetary Fund.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
