<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Cuts Key Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The National Bank of the Czech
Republic will lower key interest rates in the financial market
starting Tuesday, central banker Josef Tosovsky said.
</P>
<P>
The discount rate for commercial banks will be lowered from
11.5 percent to 10 percent, Tosovsky said.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates for bi-weekly, short-term loans will be cut from
13.5 percent to 12.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
A one-point cut will also be made on the lombard, or
fixed-termed advance rate, from 16 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The cut, the fifth this year, will be made to further ease the
country's stringent monetary policies, which have resulted in a
short supply of credit and funds for businesses, as well as
sagging production and exports.
</P>
<P>
The four previous cuts have brought down interest rates by a
total of 2.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The interest-cut measures have been deemed effective in
controlling the country's inflation, which was 8.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said that in order to spur effective economic
growth, the country will consider relaxing the money market and
further lowering interest rates at the appropriate time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Launches Environmental Debt Program in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Spain is promoting in
Panama and other Latin American countries a sustainable
development project funded on a debt for environment swap program.
</P>
<P>
The director of Spain's Latin American cooperation office,
Jesus de Gracia, said on Tuesday that under the project, dubbed
"Araucaria", debtor countries would only have to repay part of
their debt to Spain in hard currency, using the rest to fund
environmental projects.
</P>
<P>
"The whole debt cannot be swapped, due to the fact that when
the government and Spanish (bankers) make a loan they expect it to
be repaid, so 'Araucaria' is limited," Jesus de Gracia said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the debt for environment swap program could be
studied on a case-by-case basis for special projects, but that it
could not cover the total debts of Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
De Gracia said that the Spanish government had created a
70-million-dollar-fund with a five-year grace period for the
program managed by its international cooperation offices.
</P>
<P>
He said the program will allow debtor countries to create their
own fund in local currency for environmental development projects
to raise living standards for their populations.
</P>
<P>
Panama is using the program for an ecological tourism
development program on the Pacific island of Coiba - previously a
prison center. Other regions benefiting from the program include
Ecuador, Peru, Bolivia, Costa Rica and the Dominican Republic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
