<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Investments in Argentina Total 2.3 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The British investment in
Argentina totaled 2.3 billion U.S. dollars in the 1994-97 period,
according to a private investment fund report.
</P>
<P>
A total of 28 percent of the investments went into oil and gas
extraction, refining and distribution sectors, while 26 percent
went into banks and insurance companies, and 22 percent funded the
chemicals industry, the report said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors with significant British investments are mining,
food, drink, tobacco and electric sectors.
</P>
<P>
A total of 67 British companies are currently based in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade increased from 378 million dollars in 1992 to
over one billion dollars in 1997, with a trade deficit registered
by Argentina, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine products which register the most important sales
in England are meat, fish, milk products, fruit, coffee, and
cereals.
</P>
<P>
British exports to Argentina include drinks, vinegar, mineral
oils, non-organic chemicals, pharmaceutical products and plastic
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
