<HEADLINE> Colombian Unions End 21-Day Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Union leaders representing more
than 80,000 state workers signed a pact on Tuesday with the
government ending a three-week strike that started on October 7.
</P>
<P>
Colombian President Andres Pastrana said he was satisfied with
the agreement, which raises the workers' salaries by 15 percent or
one percentage point more than the government's first offer.
</P>
<P>
The government also offered to compensate workers for the hours
they lost during the country's longest strike and pledged not to
retaliate against strike leaders.
</P>
<P>
Teachers in state-run schools were also granted a 16 percent
pay raise.
</P>
<P>
The workers have promised to return to work on
Wednesday. 
</P>
