<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Players, Owners Studying Hybrid Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
So far, the situation started to turn hopeful, at least
heading to a compromise.
</P>
<P>
Each side made a case for its position in the labor dispute
and presented models and projections for what could happen 3-5
years down the road.
</P>
<P>
The owners backed off their insistence on having a hard salary
cap. "We need a system that eventually gets to where there's a
set percentage for the players and a set percentage for the
owners," deputy commissioner Russ Granik said. "I don't think it
has to be a hard cap, and in fact some of the things we're
talking about now are not hard cap."
</P>
<P>
The owners' shift in position was downplayed by the union, but
some agents still think it is a good sign.
</P>
<P>
"The best thing is we have some sort of an agreement on basic
principles," said Danny Schayes, a member of the union's
negotiating team. "Right now, we're talking about a hybrid
system. The first couple of years it would work one way, for
another couple of years it would work another way if the first
way didn't work. At least we're finding some common ground."
</P>
<P>
The sides agreed to meet through the week.
</P>
<P>
The league was asking to operate under a luxury tax system for
the next three seasons, with a fallback system of a harder salary
cap for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The union was asking for a tax system lasting two years, with
the fallback system lasting another two years, Schayes said.
</P>
<P>
"Instead of absolute cost certainty, there would be mechanisms
that give the owners a very good shot at costs within a certain
range. So it's a good compromise in that area," Schayes said.
</P>
<P>
The league's full board is expected to meet on Wednesday.
Union executive director Billy Hunter hopes to have the entire
membership meet with owners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
