<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's New Government Wins Senate Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ROME, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Italy's new government, which
will be led by Massimo D'Alema, easily won a confidence vote in
the Senate on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The victory, which garnered 188 votes to 116 with only one
abstention, means the government is now officially up and running.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema, a communist-turned-social democrat, was sworn in a
week ago as the head of Italy's 56th government since World War
II. He won a confidence vote in the lower house last Friday.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema's predecessor, Romano Prodi, resigned on October 9
after losing a lower house confidence vote. 
</P>
