<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: NATO's Next Move From Ultimatum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- NATO faces as tough a test as
does Belgrade when the clock ticks toward the final hours of the
ultimatum, already extended for a 10-more-day grace period,
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
NATO decision makers, due to meet later Tuesday, are faced with
the option of whether or not delivering on the air strike first
a*
 two
officers reached an agreement with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and Yugoslav Army Chief of Staff Momcilo Perisic.
</P>
<P>
Cook said, "If he (the Yugoslav president) keeps to this
agreement, then that will certainly be a significant advance."
</P>
<P>
Reports of massive withdrawal of troops and police units came
in the last two days while member countries of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe were busy grouping the
2,000-member verification mission, of which the advance team
already reached Kosovo, and international humanitarian
organizations were hurrying relief materials to the home-returning
refugees and those still remaining in makeshift shelters in the
open with winter fast approaching.
</P>
<P>
Less likely it is therefore for NATO now to punctuate the
compliance that is now developing or the humanitarian relief work
so essential to the refugees, both the foundations for NATO's
activation order without a mandate via United Nations Security
Council Resolutions (UNSCRs).
</P>
<P>
NATO pronounced that it was resorting to military intervention
to force Belgrade to comply fully with UNSCRs in a verifiable
manner, so it should not be completely out-of-expectation that
NATO chooses to allow still more time for compliance to develop
the way it explains fit.
</P>
<P>
The British foreign secretary stressed Monday that possible
option of further extension of the ultimatum should not be seen as
a concession to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
But problem then arises as to when the next grace period comes
to its end.
</P>
<P>
NATO, therefore, is likely to alter its timed ultimatum to an
open-ended menace and the unlimited ultimatum gives the allies
more leeway to move both forward and back.
</P>
<P>
It is also less likely for NATO now to lift the activation
order, for that will tarnish its image in the increasingly
face-saving tussle and influence otherwise on its crisis
management strategy still in the make.
</P>
<P>
What NATO is reluctant to do is to take back the words it has
uttered without their having taken any measurable effect and what
it likes has got to be a move that maneuvers the Western military
alliance to a foot-hold that offers both comfort and confidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
