<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Country Parks in Eastern Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Dawn or dusk, people in the
village of Yangjialou can be seen chatting, playing chess, or
strolling through a local park with tiny bridges, pavilions,
lawns, and pools.
</P>
<P>
These scenes have become common in the Chinese province of
Zhejiang, one of the most developed eastern coastal areas in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Villagers who are better-off now see the park as the place to
spend their leisure time.
</P>
<P>
"I used to think that strolling in a park was only the
privilege of urbanites," said Jin Atu, a local man who is in his
60s and who now spends much of his time in a nearby park.
</P>
<P>
For farmers, parks are as important as roads and bridges, says
a local government official, because they are a way to improve
villagers' standard of living and change their lifestyle, and many
places in the province have built or are planning to build parks.
</P>
<P>
"With a park, my village is more like a city now." said Hu
Yinjuan, who was walking in a 6.7-hectare park in the town of
Qixian.
</P>
<P>
One of the advantages of having a park, according to Lou
Baozhong in the village of Yangjialou, is to have a place for
farmers to go when they are freed from the day's farm work.
</P>
<P>
A village is different from city, he explains, because normally
a village has no commercial or other colorful street to walk
along, so, in the past, they used to have nothing to do but work
in the fields or kill time by chatting with neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Parks also help introduce a healthier life and may also do
something more - bring in tourists.
</P>
<P>
One park in the village of Minzhu has 300,000 tourists this
year, 80 percent of them from neighboring villages.
</P>
<P>
"We have spent 3.5 million yuan on the park and now we are
going to spend five million yuan next year to improve it," said
the park manager.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
