<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Research Details Software Industry's Economic Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 27 (Xinhua) -- A report released Tuesday
said that the software industry has generated more 619,000 jobs
and 7.2 billion U.S. dollars in tax revenues in the United States
over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Globally, the industry racked up total sales of 135.4 billion
dollars last year, said the report released by the Business
Software Alliance (BSA), the voice of the world's leading software
developers.
</P>
<P>
The report, Contributions of the Packaged Software Industry to
the Global Economy, was conducted by the U.S. market analysis firm
Pricewaterhouse Coopers. It provides further evidence that the
industry is one of the rapidly growing sectors of the world
economy and is driving job creation across the globe, the BSA
said.
</P>
<P>
"This new report confirms the fact that the software industry
has emerged as a powerful engine of economic growth both in the
United States and abroad," BSA president and CEO Robert Holleyman
said in a statement. "In addition, the industry is creating high
wage jobs all over the world. In the United States, software
industry workers enjoy more than twice the average level of wages
earned by other workers in the economy."
</P>
<P>
Software industry revenues outside the United States alone will
reach 116.9 billion dollars by 2001. Industry growth will yield an
additional more than 320,000 jobs by 2001, providing employment
for 1.06 million people outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
For the U.S. economy, direct employment in the software
industry will reach 1.03 million jobs by 2005.
</P>
<P>
The report also shows that software piracy results in lost
government revenues. A key finding points out that successful
efforts to eliminate software piracy by 2005 could allow the
software industry to raise nearly 25 billion dollars in additional
government revenues worldwide. Between 1996 and 1997, the software
industry and supporting industries contributed over 28 billion
dollars in tax revenues to world governments. Of that, 7.2 billion
dollars was paid to U.S. federal, state and local governments.
</P>
</TEXT>
