<HEADLINE> U.S. Stocks Tumble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. stocks fell on Tuesday
amid investors' concerns about the near-term economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 66.17 to close at 8366.04
and other market indicators also posted declines, including the
indexes of the best performers in recent sessions such as small
and technology companies.
</P>
<P>
The Dow of 30 blue-chip companies saw a rise of 66 points in
morning trading, but it retreated amid profit-taking and ended in
the third consecutive fall since Saturday with a combined loss of
167 points after soaring nearly 600 points for the previous
seven-sessions.
</P>
<P>
The New York-based research group of Conference Board reported
on Tuesday that consumer confidence in the U.S. fell to a nearly
two years' low in October amid increasing concerns about global
economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures show that the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell
6.97 to 1065.35 and the technology-laced Nasdaq composite index
fell 7.35 to 1717.63.
</P>
<P>
The New York Stock Exchange composite index fell 2.24 to
527.77, the American Stock Exchange composite index fell 2.17 to
632.38 and the Russell 2000 of small companies fell 0.57 to
371.50.
</P>
<P>
Decliners beat advancers 10-9 with trading volume up to 757
million shares from 600 million previously on the NYSE. 
</P>
