president of the 15-member council, Jeremy Greenstock of the
United Kingdom, said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the press here after the council's
closed-door consultations, Greenstock said the council members
"welcomed the resumption of political dialogue between the two
leaders and urged the governments to maintain that dialogue, and
implement the confidence-building measures that were agreed in
July."
</P>
<P>
The rebel activities near the border areas between Sierra Leone
and Liberia have given rise to increased tension between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council praised the work of the U.N. Observer
Mission in Sierra Leone, the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS), the U.N. High Commission for Refugees and other
governments and agencies involved in the west African country,
Greenstock said.
</P>
<P>
The council members encouraged leaders of the two neighboring
African countries to use the opportunity of the ECOWAS summit in
Abuja, capital of Nigeria, this week to build confidence between
the two nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Security Council called on member states in the
donor community to make further contributions to assist the
deployment of the west African peace-keepers, known as the ECOMOG,
in Sierra Leone, to support the government's disarmament,
demobilization and reintegration program, and to address the
humanitarian needs of the country, he added. 
