<HEADLINE> New Technology Turns Agro-Waste into Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. researchers from BC
International Corporation and the University of Florida, use
genetically engineered bacteria to make ethanol, a fuel for
vehicles, from agricultural wastes, said a report from the New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
They said grape vine waste, corn stalks, rice hulls, waste
paper, tree trimmings and yard waste could be used as row material
for the new technology.
</P>
<P>
BC International Corporation will build a plant in Jennings,
Louisiana, to produce ethanol in a big-scale and commercial way.
The plant will run on bagasse, a part of the sugar cane plant
usually considered useless as well as rice hulls, a currently
useless part of the rice plant.
</P>
<P>
The "bio-refinery", the report said, will turn cellulose in
the waste into sugar and then into ethanol by genetically
engineered bacteria KO11 with the help of acetic acid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
