<HEADLINE> Albright Says NATO Still Could Use Force Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Tuesday that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) would
move quickly to use force against Yugoslavia if its forces are
back to Kosovo to fight ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright made the statements
at a special briefing on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO allies were preparing to assemble a rapid-reaction force
in the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia to be ready to
intervene if Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic sent troops
against civilians again, said Albright.
</P>
<P>
It would not take long to persuade the allies to renew their
threat to attack Serb positions since all of them were pretty much
in agreement Milosevic could not be permitted to menace civilians
again, she added.
</P>
<P>
Albright said sending in a rapid-deployment would require
Macedonia's approval. "Its purpose will be to ensure that alliance
forces are on call to respond if needed," she added.
</P>
<P>
The secretary stressed that NATO had not suspended its threat
to use force, but rather did not act on the threat now.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton, meanwhile, talked by telephone with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and other allied leaders about
the need "to keep Milosevic's feet to the fire as we assess his
compliance and his willingness to stay in compliance," a U.S.
official said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was briefed by Sandy Berger, his assistant for national
security, on Milosevic's actions.
</P>
<P>
Albright said Milosevic's withdrawal of troops and police
"should result in a safer and more secure climate" for refugees to
return to their homes, and that many had already.
</P>
<P>
"The result, if all goes well, will be the prevention of
further humanitarian catastrophe," she said.
</P>
<P>
However, Albright said, a political crisis remained, that alone
could be resolved in negotiations between the Serbs and ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic Albanians are seeking independence from Yugoslavia
while the Clinton administration supports more autonomy is given
to the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"Not even NATO military force can resolve the tensions,
rivalries and disagreements that are at the heart of the problems
of Kosovo," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
To help negotiations, she said, the United States had sent "a
clear message" to leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army not to
attempt to take military advantage of the Serb pullback.
</P>
<P>
"Neither side can achieve a military victory in Kosovo,"
Albright said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
