<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Health Sector Development in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday
approved an interest-free credit of 100 million U.S. dollars to
support the first five-year phase of Ethiopia's 20-year health
sector development program.
</P>
<P>
The major objective of the program is to improve health
services and extend their coverage to a larger number of
Ethiopians. The program is designed to develop a system to deliver
comprehensive and integrated primary health care services to
communities, with a focus on reaching rural and other under-served
groups, especially women.
</P>
<P>
The program includes the construction and rehabilitation of
more than 400 health centers and hospitals, the training of health
care workers and administrators, public information and outreach
as well as decentralization of the health care sector.
</P>
<P>
During fiscal 1998 ending June 30 this year, Ethiopia was the
largest African borrower from the World Bank, and also among the
top 10 borrowers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The bank committed 669 million dollars to the East African
country for projects to meet other basic development priorities,
which include 309 million dollars for roads, 200 million dollars
for the energy sector, 100 million dollars for education and 60
million dollars for agricultural research and training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
