<HEADLINE> Clinton: NATO Keeps Vigilant on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday welcomed the withdrawal of Serb troops from Kosovo but said
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) would remain
vigilant to ensure Belgrade fully complied with U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
"This is a chance, not a guarantee," Clinton said at a White
House event in which he warned Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic he must "stay in compliance" with the rules spelled out
by the international community.
</P>
<P>
A senior U.S. defense official, who tracked the events in
Yugoslavia over the past months, told reporters that Serbia is
withdrawing troops and cooperating with the monitors.
</P>
<P>
"I would be pleased to say today that we see substantial and
significant movement by the army and the police, both from Kosovo
to Serbia proper, where they're required to do so, and back into
garrison, especially for the armored and mechanized units of the
Pristina corps in Kosovo," said the official.
</P>
<P>
"Essentially, our attach's and also the Kosovo Diplomatic
Observer Mission report significant cooperation by the Serbs
today, as they've been able to inspect these units, as they
departed their field deployment areas and moved back into
garrisons," added the official.
</P>
<P>
The official, who declined to be named, said the cease-fire in
the region "is generally holding."
</P>
<P>
"We also have indications that the Serbian air defense forces
are beginning to come back into their garrisons, as required by
NATO. That's not complete yet, of course, but there is some
significant movement in that direction," the official noted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, State Secretary Madeleine Albright said NATO allies
were preparing to assemble a rapid-reaction force in the former
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia to be ready to intervene if
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic sends troops against
civilians again.
</P>
<P>
It will not take long to persuade the allies to renew their
threat to attack Serb positions since all of them are pretty much
in agreement Milosevic cannot be permitted to menace civilians
again, she told a briefing.
</P>
<P>
Albright said sending in a rapid-deployment would require
Macedonia's approval. "Its purpose will be to ensure that alliance
forces are on call to respond if needed," she added.
</P>
<P>
The secretary stressed that NATO had not suspended its threat
to use force, but rather did not act on the threat now.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton, meanwhile, talked by telephone to
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and other allied leaders about
the need "to keep Milosevic's feet to the fire as we assess his
compliance and his willingness to stay in compliance," a U.S.
official said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was briefed by Sandy Berger, his assistant for national
security, on Milosevic's actions.
</P>
<P>
Albright said Milosevic's withdrawal of troops and police
"should result in a safer and more secure climate" for refugees to
return to their homes, and that many have already.
</P>
<P>
"The result, if all goes well, will be the prevention of
further humanitarian catastrophe," she said.
</P>
<P>
However, Albright said, a political crisis remains, that alone
can be resolved in negotiations between the Serbs and ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic Albanians are seeking independence from Yugoslavia
while the Clinton administration supports more autonomy was given
to the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"Not even NATO military force can resolve the tensions,
rivalries and disagreements that are at the heart of the problems
of Kosovo," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
To help negotiations, she said, the United States has sent "a
clear message" to leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army not to
attempt to take military advantage of the Serb pullback.
</P>
<P>
"Neither side can achieve a military victory in Kosovo,"
Albright said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Proposes Plan for Breaking W. Sahara Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N.
secretary-general, Kofi Annan, on Tuesday proposed a green light
to voter registration of members of three Western Sahara tribal
groups involved in a dispute that has held up a referendum on the
the future of the territory.
</P>
<P>
The referendum is to decide whether Western Sahara should be
incorporated into Morocco, which controls most of the former
Spanish colony, or become independent, as sought by the Polisario
Front, whose base camps are in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The vote was originally set for January 1992, following a
U.N.-monitored ceasefire that went into effect in September 1991.
But the referendum has been repeatedly delayed because of
differences between Morocco and Polisario over who should be
eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
Annan reported in September that voter registration, as part of
a U.N. peace plan, had been completed and more than 147,000
applicants identified. Still unresolved was the eligibility of
some 65,000 members of three disputed tribal groupings.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council is scheduled to consider Annan's
report on Wednesday morning, Jeremy Greenstock, president of the
15-member council, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Morocco maintained that all members of those groups had a right
to be identified to determine their eligibility to vote. However,
Polisario said none had that right except for those listed in a
1974 Spanish census of the territory, and their immediate
families.
</P>
<P>
To break the deadlock, Annan said in his latest report: "I have
decided to present my own arbitration in order to move ahead on
this issue,"
</P>
<P>
"In order to avoid taking any arbitrary decision which might
lead to the exclusion of persons who are eligible to vote
... I see no other alternative than to ask the Identification
Commission to proceed now to consider requests from any applicants
from the tribal groupings in question who wish to present
themselves individually, in order to verify whether they have the
right to vote," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
He referred to the possibility of holding the referendum in
December 1999 -- a year later than the most recent target date of
December 7 this year.
</P>
<P>
Annan said a U.N. delegation which recently visited the area
submitted documents to Morocco and Polisario regarding the
identification of individuals from the disputed groups and an
outline of the next stage in the U.N. plan.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general, who will visit the region next month,
said final agreement of the two parties would be needed by
mid-November so that the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR), Sadako Ogata of Japan, could prepare to receive refugees
wishing to return to Western Sahara. Voter identification of
members of the disputed groups could begin on December 1.
</P>
<P>
Annan recommended extending until April 30, 1999, the mandate
of the 470-member U.N. Mission for the Referendum in Western
Sahara (MINURSO), which has been stationed in the territory for
the past seven years. Its current mandate expires on October 31.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he would make recommendations to the Security
Council in December for strengthening the force, to carry out
additional duties leading up to the planned referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981028.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
