<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinshasa Deals With Rwanda, Uganda, Not Rebels: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister of Democratic
Congo Jean Charles Okoto said here Tuesday that his government
only deals with Rwanda and Uganda instead of the rebels fighting
to topple President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
These remarks were made by the Congolese minister when he
gave a news briefing Tuesday afternoon during the intervals of a
regional ministerial meeting held here from October 26 to 27,
during which a draft cease-fire was adopted in principle to end
the Congo (K) crisis.
</P>
<P>
When asked by Xinhua whether any cease-fire on the crisis
would be meaningful without direct negotiations with the rebels,
Okoto said if the rebels wanted to come to power they should do
it through elections since President Kabila had set an agenda for
democratization in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said at present the Congolese government only wanted to
negotiate with Rwanda and Uganda, accusing them of invading to
back the rebels and urged the two countries to withdraw their
forces from Congo (K) immediately.
</P>
<P>
"We are negotiating with the aggressors, namely Rwanda and
Uganda. Right now we can not even talk about the rebels because
there is no rebel in Congo," said the minister, adding, "we need
them to leave our country immediately."
</P>
<P>
However, Bizima Karaha, a former Congolese foreign minister,
who led the rebel delegation but was denied access to the
meeting, declared that unless the Congolese government sat down
and talked with the rebels, there would be no solution to the
Congo (K) crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The Congolese problem must be resolved by the Congolese
people themselves," he told reporter outside the meeting venue
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
As regard to the troops sent by Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola,
Okoto said people could not treat them equally with the troops
from Rwanda and Uganda. He explained that those troops fighting
to help Kabila were "invited" by the Congolese government as
their "guests".
</P>
<P>
But at the meeting, Rwanda firmly denied all the Kinshasa
accusations, saying that up till now it has never admitted any
military presence in Congo (K). While Uganda, who claimed to have
security interests in the eastern part of Congo (K), said its
forces were sent sthere to check its rebels aiming to topple the
Kampala government.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released at the end of the Lusaka ministerial
meeting, Ugandan Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Amama
Mbabazi expressed Ugandan government's position on the Congo (K)
crisis that all foreign forces should leave that country.
</P>
<P>
"Our view is that all foreign troops should leave the DRC. The
withdrawal should be done after a cease-fire and when neutral
multi-national forces have taken up positions in the DRC to
supervise strict observance of the cease-fire and ensure security
of the neighboring countries," Mbabazi said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the problem in Congo (K) was essentially
"political" and therefore required a political settlement between
Kabila's government and the entire Congolese opposition.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka ministerial meeting attracted more than 130
delegates including foreign and defense ministers from 14 African
countries, in particular, those key players such as Zimbabwe,
Namibia, Angola, Congo (K), Uganda and Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
